# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: immune-response
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The **adaptive immune system** (**AIS**), also known as the **acquired immune system** or **specific immune system**, is a subsystem of the immune system that is composed of specialized cells, organs, and processes that eliminate pathogens specifically.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The acquired immune system is one of the two main immunity strategies found in vertebrates (the other being the innate immune system).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Like the innate system, the adaptive immune system includes both humoral immunity components and cell-mediated immunity components and destroys invading pathogens.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Unlike the innate immune system, which is pre-programmed to react to common broad categories of pathogen, the adaptive immune system is highly specific to each particular pathogen the body has encountered.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Adaptive immunity creates immunological memory after an initial response to a specific pathogen, and leads to an enhanced response to future encounters with that pathogen.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Antibodies are a critical part of the adaptive immune system.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Adaptive immunity can provide long-lasting protection, sometimes for the person's entire lifetime.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] For example, someone who recovers from measles is now protected against measles for their lifetime; in other cases it does not provide lifetime protection, as with chickenpox.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] This process of adaptive immunity is the basis of vaccination.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The cells that carry out the adaptive immune response are white blood cells known as lymphocytes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] B cells and T cells, two different types of lymphocytes, carry out the main activities: antibody responses, and cell-mediated immune response.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In antibody responses, B cells are activated to secrete antibodies, which are proteins also known as immunoglobulins.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Antibodies travel through the bloodstream and bind to the foreign antigen causing it to inactivate, which does not allow the antigen to bind to the host.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Antigens are any substances that elicit the adaptive immune response.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Sometimes the adaptive system is unable to distinguish harmful from harmless foreign molecules; the effects of this may be hayfever, asthma, or any other allergy.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In adaptive immunity, pathogen-specific receptors are "acquired" during the lifetime of the organism (whereas in innate immunity pathogen-specific receptors are already encoded in the genome).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] This acquired response is called "adaptive" because it prepares the body's immune system for future challenges (though it can actually also be maladaptive when it results in allergies or autoimmunity).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The system is highly adaptable because of two factors.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] First, somatic hypermutation is a process of accelerated random genetic mutations in the antibody-coding genes, which allows antibodies with novel specificity to be created.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Second, V(D)J recombination randomly selects one variable (V), one diversity (D), and one joining (J) region for genetic recombination and discards the rest, which produces a highly unique combination of antigen-receptor gene segments in each lymphocyte.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] This mechanism allows a small number of genetic segments to generate a vast number of different antigen receptors, which are then uniquely expressed on each individual lymphocyte.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Since the gene rearrangement leads to an irreversible change in the DNA of each cell, all progeny (offspring) of that cell inherit genes that encode the same receptor specificity, including the memory B cells and memory T cells that are the keys to long-lived specific immunity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The term "adaptive" was first used by Robert Good in reference to antibody responses in frogs as a synonym for "acquired immune response" in 1964.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Good acknowledged he used the terms as synonyms but explained only that he preferred to use the term "adaptive".
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The term "adaptive" as used in immunology is problematic as acquired immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the physiological sense.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Indeed, both acquired and innate immune responses can be both adaptive and maladaptive in the evolutionary sense.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Most textbooks today, following the early use by Janeway, use "adaptive" almost exclusively and noting in glossaries that the term is synonymous with "acquired".
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The classic sense of "acquired immunity" came to mean, since Tonegawa's discovery, "antigen-specific immunity mediated by somatic gene rearrangements that create clone-defining antigen receptors".
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In the last decade, the term "adaptive" has been increasingly applied to another class of immune response not so-far associated with somatic gene rearrangements.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] These include expansion of natural killer (NK) cells with so-far unexplained specificity for antigens, expansion of NK cells expressing germ-line encoded receptors, and activation of other innate immune cells to an activated state that confers a short-term "immune memory".
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In this sense, "adaptive immunity" more closely resembles the concept of "activated state" or "heterostasis", thus returning in sense to the physiological sense of "adaptation" to environmental changes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Acquired immunity is triggered in vertebrates when a pathogen evades the innate immune system and (1) generates a threshold level of antigen and (2) generates "stranger" or "danger" signals activating dendritic cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In humans, it takes 4–7 days for the adaptive immune system to mount a significant response.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] T and B lymphocytes are the cells of the adaptive immune system.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The human body has about 2 trillion lymphocytes, which are 20–40% of white blood cells; their total mass is about the same as the brain or liver.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The peripheral bloodstream contains only 2% of all circulating lymphocytes; the other 98% move within tissues and the lymphatic system, which includes the lymph nodes and spleen.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In humans, approximately 1–2% of the lymphocyte pool recirculates each hour to increase the opportunity for the cells to encounter the specific pathogen and antigen that they react to.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] B cells and T cells are derived from the same multipotent hematopoietic stem cells, and look identical to one another until after they are activated.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] B cells play a large role in the humoral immune response, whereas T cells are intimately involved in cell-mediated immune responses.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In all vertebrates except Agnatha, B cells and T cells are produced by stem cells in the bone marrow.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] T cell progenitors then migrate from the bone marrow to the thymus, where they develop further.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Acquired immunity relies on the capacity of immune cells to distinguish between the body's own cells and unwanted invaders.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The host's cells express "self" antigens.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] These antigens are different from those on the surface of bacteria or on the surface of virus-infected host cells ("non-self" or "foreign" antigens).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The acquired immune response is triggered by recognizing foreign antigen in the cellular context of an activated dendritic cell.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), all cells are capable of presenting antigen through the function of major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Some cells are specially equipped to present antigen, and to prime naive T cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Dendritic cells, B-cells, and macrophages are equipped with special "co-stimulatory" ligands recognized by co-stimulatory receptors on T cells, and are termed professional antigen-presenting cells (APCs).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Several T cells subgroups can be activated by professional APCs, and each type of T cell is specially equipped to deal with each unique toxin or microbial pathogen.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The type of T cell activated, and the type of response generated, depends, in part, on the context in which the APC first encountered the antigen.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Dendritic cells engulf exogenous pathogens, such as bacteria, parasites or toxins in the tissues and then migrate, via chemotactic signals, to the T cell-enriched lymph nodes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] During migration, dendritic cells undergo a process of maturation in which they lose most of their ability to engulf other pathogens, and develop an ability to communicate with T-cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The dendritic cell uses enzymes to chop the pathogen into smaller pieces, called antigens.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In the lymph node, the dendritic cell displays these non-self antigens on its surface by coupling them to a receptor called the major histocompatibility complex, or MHC (also known in humans as human leukocyte antigen (HLA)).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] This MHC-antigen complex is recognized by T-cells passing through the lymph node.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Exogenous antigens are usually displayed on MHC class II molecules, which activate CD4+T helper cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Endogenous antigens are produced by intracellular bacteria and viruses replicating within a host cell.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The host cell uses enzymes to digest virally associated proteins and displays these pieces on its surface to T-cells by coupling them to MHC.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Endogenous antigens are typically displayed on MHC class I molecules, and activate CD8+ cytotoxic T-cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] With the exception of non-nucleated cells (including erythrocytes), MHC class I is expressed by all host cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Cytotoxic T cells (also known as TC, cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs), or killer T cells) are a sub-group of T cells that induce the death of cells that are infected with viruses (and other pathogens), or are otherwise damaged or dysfunctional.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Naive cytotoxic T cells are activated when their T-cell receptor (TCR) strongly interacts with a peptide-bound MHC class I molecule.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] This affinity depends on the type and orientation of the antigen/MHC complex, and is what keeps the CTL and infected cell bound together.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Once activated, the CTL undergoes a process called clonal selection, in which it gains functions and divides rapidly to produce an army of "armed" effector cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The activated CTL then travels throughout the body searching for cells that bear that unique MHC class I + peptide.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] When exposed to these infected or dysfunctional somatic cells, effector CTLs release perforin and granulysin: cytotoxins that form pores in the target cell's plasma membrane, allowing ions and water to flow into the infected cell and causing it to burst or lyse.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] CTLs release granzyme, a serine protease encapsulated in a granule that enters cells via pores to induce apoptosis (cell death).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] To limit extensive tissue damage during an infection, CTL activation is tightly controlled and in general requires a very strong MHC/antigen activation signal, or additional activation signals provided by "helper" T-cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] On resolution of the infection, most effector cells die and phagocytes clear them away—but a few of these cells remain as memory cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] On a later encounter with the same antigen, these memory cells quickly differentiate into effector cells, dramatically shortening the time required to mount an effective response.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] CD4+ lymphocytes, also called "helper" T cells, are immune response mediators, and play an important role in establishing and maximizing the capabilities of the acquired immune response.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] These cells have no cytotoxic or phagocytic activity; and cannot kill infected cells or clear pathogens, but, in essence "manage" the immune response, by directing other cells to perform these tasks.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Helper T cells express T cell receptors (TCR) that recognize antigen bound to Class II MHC molecules.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The activation of a naive helper T-cell causes it to release cytokines, which influences the activity of many cell types, including the APC (Antigen-Presenting Cell) that activated it.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Helper T-cells require a much milder activation stimulus than cytotoxic T cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Helper T cells can provide extra signals that "help" activate cytotoxic cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Classically, two types of effector CD4+ T helper cell responses can be induced by a professional APC, designated Th1 and Th2, each designed to eliminate different types of pathogens.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The factors that dictate whether an infection triggers a Th1 or Th2 type response are not fully understood, but the response generated does play an important role in the clearance of different pathogens.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The Th1 response is characterized by the production of Interferon-gamma, which activates the bactericidal activities of macrophages, and induces B cells to make opsonizing (marking for phagocytosis) and complement-fixing antibodies, and leads to *cell-mediated immunity*.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In general, Th1 responses are more effective against intracellular pathogens (viruses and bacteria that are inside host cells).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The Th2 response is characterized by the release of Interleukin 5, which induces eosinophils in the clearance of parasites.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Th2 also produce Interleukin 4, which facilitates B cell isotype switching.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In general, Th2 responses are more effective against extracellular bacteria, parasites including helminths and toxins.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Like cytotoxic T cells, most of the CD4+ helper cells die on resolution of infection, with a few remaining as CD4+ memory cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Increasingly, there is strong evidence from mouse and human-based scientific studies of a broader diversity in CD4+ effector T helper cell subsets.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Regulatory T (Treg) cells, have been identified as important negative regulators of adaptive immunity as they limit and suppress the immune system to control aberrant immune responses to self-antigens; an important mechanism in controlling the development of autoimmune diseases.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Follicular helper T (Tfh) cells are another distinct population of effector CD4+ T cells that develop from naive T cells post-antigen activation.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Tfh cells are specialized in helping B cell humoral immunity as they are uniquely capable of migrating to follicular B cells in secondary lymphoid organs and provide them positive paracrine signals to enable the generation and recall production of high-quality affinity-matured antibodies.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Similar to Tregs, Tfh cells also play a role in immunological tolerance as an abnormal expansion of Tfh cell numbers can lead to unrestricted autoreactive antibody production causing severe systemic autoimmune disorders.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The relevance of CD4+ T helper cells is highlighted during an HIV infection.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] HIV is able to subvert the immune system by specifically attacking the CD4+ T cells, precisely the cells that could drive the clearance of the virus, but also the cells that drive immunity against all other pathogens encountered during an organism's lifetime.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Gamma delta T cells (γδ T cells) possess an alternative T cell receptor (TCR) as opposed to CD4+ and CD8+ αβ T cells and share characteristics of helper T cells, cytotoxic T cells and natural killer cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Like other 'unconventional' T cell subsets bearing invariant TCRs, such as CD1d-restricted natural killer T cells, γδ T cells exhibit characteristics that place them at the border between innate and acquired immunity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] On one hand, γδ T cells may be considered a component of adaptive immunity in that they rearrange TCR genes via V(D)J recombination, which also produces junctional diversity, and develop a memory phenotype.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] On the other hand, however, the various subsets may also be considered part of the innate immune system where a restricted TCR or NK receptors may be used as a pattern recognition receptor.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] For example, according to this paradigm, large numbers of Vγ9/Vδ2 T cells respond within hours to common molecules produced by microbes, and highly restricted intraepithelial Vδ1 T cells respond to stressed epithelial cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] B Cells are the major cells involved in the creation of antibodies that circulate in blood plasma and lymph, known as humoral immunity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Antibodies (also known as immunoglobulin, Ig), are large Y-shaped proteins used by the immune system to identify and neutralize foreign objects.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In mammals, there are five types of antibody: IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM, differing in biological properties; each has evolved to handle different kinds of antigens.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Upon activation, B cells produce antibodies, each of which recognize a unique antigen, and neutralizing specific pathogens.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Like the T cell, B cells express a unique B cell receptor (BCR), in this case, a membrane-bound antibody molecule.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] All the BCR of any one clone of B cells recognizes and binds to only one particular antigen.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] A critical difference between B cells and T cells is how each cell "sees" an antigen.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] T cells recognize their cognate antigen in a processed form – as a peptide in the context of an MHC molecule, whereas B cells recognize antigens in their native form.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Once a B cell encounters its cognate (or specific) antigen (and receives additional signals from a helper T cell (predominately Th2 type)), it further differentiates into an effector cell, known as a plasma cell.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Plasma cells are short-lived cells (2–3 days) that secrete antibodies.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] These antibodies bind to antigens, making them easier targets for phagocytes, and trigger the complement cascade.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] About 10% of plasma cells survive to become long-lived antigen-specific memory B cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Already primed to produce specific antibodies, these cells can be called upon to respond quickly if the same pathogen re-infects the host, while the host experiences few, if any, symptoms.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Primitive jawless vertebrates, such as the lamprey and hagfish, have an adaptive immune system that shows 3 different cell lineages, each sharing a common origin with B cells, αβ T cells, and innate-like γΔ T cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Instead of the classical antibodies and T cell receptors, these animals possess a large array of molecules called variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs for short) that, like the antigen receptors of jawed vertebrates, are produced from only a small number (one or two) of genes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] These molecules are believed to bind pathogenic antigens in a similar way to antibodies, and with the same degree of specificity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] For a long time it was thought that insects and other invertebrates possess only innate immune system.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] However, in recent years some of the basic hallmarks of adaptive immunity have been discovered in insects.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Those traits are immune memory and specificity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Although the hallmarks are present the mechanisms are different from those in vertebrates.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Immune memory in insects was discovered through the phenomenon of priming.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] When insects are exposed to non-lethal dose or heat killed bacteria they are able to develop a memory of that infection that allows them to withstand otherwise lethal dose of the same bacteria they were exposed to before.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Unlike in vertebrates, insects do not possess cells specific for adaptive immunity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Instead those mechanisms are mediated by hemocytes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Hemocytes function similarly to phagocytes and after priming they are able to more effectively recognize and engulf the pathogen.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] It was also shown that it is possible to transfer the memory into offspring.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] For example, in honeybees if the queen is infected with bacteria then the newly born workers have enhanced abilities in fighting with the same bacteria.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Other experimental model based on red flour beetle also showed pathogen specific primed memory transfer into offspring from both mothers and fathers.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The most commonly accepted theory of this specificity is based on the *Dscam* gene.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The *Dscam* gene, which mediates phagocytosis in some insects, contains three variable Ig domains.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] These domains can be alternatively spliced, producing a large number of possible isoforms.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] It has been shown that after exposure to different pathogens, different isoforms of Dscam are produced, and that these isoforms associate and defend against bacteria in an isoform-specific manner.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Another mechanism that supports the specificity of insect immunity is RNA interference (RNAi).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] RNAi is a form of antiviral immunity with high specificity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] It has several different pathways that all end with the virus being unable to replicate.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] One of the pathways is siRNA in which long double stranded RNA is cut into pieces that serve as templates for protein complex Ago2-RISC that finds and degrades complementary RNA of the virus.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] MiRNA pathway in cytoplasm binds to Ago1-RISC complex and functions as a template for viral RNA degradation.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Last one is piRNA where small RNA binds to the Piwi protein family and controls transposones and other mobile elements.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Despite the research the exact mechanisms responsible for immune priming and specificity in insects are not well described.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] CRISPR has a lot of short repeated sequences.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] These sequences are part of an adaptive immune system for prokaryotes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] It allows them to remember and counter the bacteriophages which prey on them.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] They work as a kind of acquired immune system for bacteria.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] When B cells and T cells are activated some become memory B cells and some memory T cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Throughout the lifetime of an animal these memory cells form a database of effective B and T lymphocytes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Upon interaction with a previously encountered antigen, the appropriate memory cells are selected and activated.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In this manner, the second and subsequent exposures to an antigen produce a stronger and faster immune response.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] This is "adaptive" in the sense that the body's immune system prepares itself for future challenges, but is "maladaptive" of course if the receptors are autoimmune.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Immunological memory can be in the form of either *passive* short-term memory or *active* long-term memory.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Passive memory is usually short-term, lasting between a few days and several months.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Newborn infants have had no prior exposure to microbes and are particularly vulnerable to infection.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Several layers of passive protection are provided by the mother.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] *In utero*, maternal IgG is transported directly across the placenta, so that, at birth, human babies have high levels of antibodies, with the same range of antigen specificities as their mother.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Breast milk contains antibodies (mainly IgA) that are transferred to the gut of the infant, protecting against bacterial infections, until the newborn can synthesize its own antibodies.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] This is passive immunity because the fetus does not actually make any memory cells or antibodies: It only borrows them.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Short-term passive immunity can also be transferred artificially from one individual to another via antibody-rich serum.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In general, active immunity is long-term and can be acquired by infection followed by B cell and T cell activation, or artificially acquired by vaccines, in a process called immunization.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Historically, infectious disease has been the leading cause of death in the human population.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Over the last century, two important factors have been developed to combat their spread: sanitation and immunization.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Immunization (commonly referred to as vaccination) is the deliberate induction of an immune response, and represents the single most effective manipulation of the immune system that scientists have developed.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Immunizations are successful because they utilize the immune system's natural specificity as well as its inducibility.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The principle behind immunization is to introduce an antigen, derived from a disease-causing organism, that stimulates the immune system to develop protective immunity against that organism, but that does not itself cause the pathogenic effects of that organism.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] An antigen (short for *anti*body *gen*erator), is defined as any substance that binds to a specific antibody and elicits an adaptive immune response.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Most viral vaccines are based on live attenuated viruses, whereas many bacterial vaccines are based on acellular components of microorganisms, including harmless toxin components.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Many antigens derived from acellular vaccines do not strongly induce an adaptive response, and most bacterial vaccines require the addition of *adjuvants* that activate the antigen-presenting cells of the innate immune system to enhance immunogenicity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Most large molecules, including virtually all proteins and many polysaccharides, can serve as antigens.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The parts of an antigen that interact with an antibody molecule or a lymphocyte receptor, are called epitopes, or antigenic determinants.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Most antigens contain a variety of epitopes and can stimulate the production of antibodies, specific T cell responses, or both.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] A very small proportion (less than 0.01%) of the total lymphocytes are able to bind to a particular antigen, which suggests that only a few cells respond to each antigen.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Even in the absence of antigen stimulation, a human can produce more than 1 trillion different antibody molecules.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Millions of genes would be required to store the genetic information that produces these receptors, but, the entire human genome contains fewer than 25,000 genes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Myriad receptors are produced through a process known as clonal selection.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] According to the clonal selection theory, at birth, an animal randomly generates a vast diversity of lymphocytes (each bearing a unique antigen receptor) from information encoded in a small family of genes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] To generate each unique antigen receptor, these genes have undergone a process called V(D)J recombination, or *combinatorial diversification*, in which one gene segment recombines with other gene segments to form a single unique gene.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] This assembly process generates the enormous diversity of receptors and antibodies, before the body ever encounters antigens, and enables the immune system to respond to an almost unlimited diversity of antigens.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Throughout an animal's lifetime, lymphocytes that can react against the antigens an animal actually encounters are selected for action—directed against anything that expresses that antigen.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The innate and acquired portions of the immune system work together, not in spite of each other.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The acquired arm, B, and T cells could not function without the innate system input.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] T cells are useless without antigen-presenting cells to activate them, and B cells are disabled without T cell help.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] On the other hand, the innate system would likely be overrun with pathogens without the specialized action of the adaptive immune response.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The cornerstone of the immune system is the recognition of "self" versus "non-self".
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Therefore, the mechanisms that protect the human fetus (which is considered "non-self") from attack by the immune system, are particularly interesting.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Although no comprehensive explanation has emerged to explain this mysterious, and often repeated, lack of rejection, two classical reasons may explain how the fetus is tolerated.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The first is that the fetus occupies a portion of the body protected by a non-immunological barrier, the uterus, which the immune system does not routinely patrol.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The second is that the fetus itself may promote local immunosuppression in the mother, perhaps by a process of active nutrient depletion.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] A more modern explanation for this induction of tolerance is that specific glycoproteins expressed in the uterus during pregnancy suppress the uterine immune response (see eu-FEDS).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] During pregnancy in viviparous mammals (all mammals except Monotremes), endogenous retroviruses (ERVs) are activated and produced in high quantities during the implantation of the embryo.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] They are currently known to possess immunosuppressive properties, suggesting a role in protecting the embryo from its mother's immune system.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The immunodepressive action was the initial normal behavior of the virus, similar to HIV.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The fusion proteins were a way to spread the infection to other cells by simply merging them with the infected one (HIV does this too).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] It is believed that the ancestors of modern viviparous mammals evolved after an infection by this virus, enabling the fetus to survive the immune system of the mother.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The human genome project found several thousand ERVs classified into 24 families.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] This theory, which builds on the existing clonal selection hypothesis and since 1974 has been developed mainly by Niels Jerne and Geoffrey W.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Hoffmann, is seen as being relevant to the understanding of the HIV pathogenesis and the search for an HIV vaccine.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] One of the most interesting developments in biomedical science during the past few decades has been elucidation of mechanisms mediating innate immunity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] One set of innate immune mechanisms is humoral, such as complement activation.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Another set comprises pattern recognition receptors such as toll-like receptors, which induce the production of interferons and other cytokines increasing resistance of cells such as monocytes to infections.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Cytokines produced during innate immune responses are among the activators of adaptive immune responses.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Antibodies exert additive or synergistic effects with mechanisms of innate immunity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Unstable HbS clusters Band-3, a major integral red cell protein; antibodies recognize these clusters and accelerate their removal by phagocytic cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Clustered Band 3 proteins with attached antibodies activate complement, and complement C3 fragments are opsonins recognized by the CR1 complement receptor on phagocytic cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] A population study has shown that the protective effect of the sickle-cell trait against falciparum malaria involves the augmentation of acquired as well as innate immune responses to the malaria parasite, illustrating the expected transition from innate to acquired immunity.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Repeated malaria infections strengthen acquired immunity and broaden its effects against parasites expressing different surface antigens.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] By school age most children have developed efficacious adaptive immunity against malaria.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] These observations raise questions about mechanisms that favor the survival of most children in Africa while allowing some to develop potentially lethal infections.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In malaria, as in other infections, innate immune responses lead into, and stimulate, adaptive immune responses.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The genetic control of innate and acquired immunity is now a large and flourishing discipline.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Humoral and cell-mediated immune responses limit malaria parasite multiplication, and many cytokines contribute to the pathogenesis of malaria as well as to the resolution of infections.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The acquired immune system evolved as an elaboration of the innate immune system.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Lymphoid cells can be identified in some pre-vertebrate deuterostomes (i.e., sea urchins).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The amphioxus is a chordate like all vertebrates.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Its genome includes many building blocks of the adaptive immune system, but none of the true hallmarks such as somatic recombination.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] There is, however, considerable expansion in LRR genes and immunoglobulin-fold genes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] There is high polymorphism among different individuals, an example of diversity in the innate immune system.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The acquired immune system, which has been best-studied in mammals, originated in jawed fish approximately 500 million years ago.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Most of the molecules, cells, tissues, and associated mechanisms of this system of defense are found in cartilaginous fishes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Lymphocyte receptors, Ig and TCR, are found in all jawed vertebrates.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The most ancient Ig class, IgM, is membrane-bound and then secreted upon stimulation of cartilaginous fish B cells.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Another isotype, shark IgW, is related to mammalian IgD.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] TCRs, both α/β and γ/δ, are found in jawed fish (cladistically including mammals).
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Most elements of the jawed fish system are in place thanks to the second round of whole-genome duplication (2R) that the jawed fish have undergone, providing an expanded repertoire of immune-related genes.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The immunoprotease genes involved in antigen processing and presentation as well as the class I and class II genes, are closely linked within the MHC of almost all studied species.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] These systems, along with RAG, were set in place quickly after 2R had happened.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The MHC region is paralogous to the Ig/TCR region.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Comparing paralogous regions allow for the reconstruction of a *primordial immune complex*.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The cartilaginous fish system does have one critical difference compared to the system of bony fish (including mammals): the gene segments that undergo V(D)J recombination in bony fish are not organized in huge clusters like they are in bony fish.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Instead, these parts are arranged as "miniclusters" and rearrangement by RAG is largely limited within these clusters.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] As a result, not as many combinations are available compared to bony fish.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The RAG transposon likely invaded a "UrIg2" immunoglobin gene, which had an unsplit VJ, in an ancestor of all extant jawed fish.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Splitting the V and J exons is adaptive, as it enables greater variation through changing the size of the CDR3 loop.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] This feature is inherited by all the descendants of UrIg2 such as Ig and TCR.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The jawless fish are vertebrates like the jawed fish, but belong on a different branch.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] In jawless fish, three subsets of lymphocytes use variable lymphocyte receptors (VLRs) for antigen binding.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The VLRs are derived from pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) of the innate immune system.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Diversity is generated by a cytosine deaminase-mediated rearrangement of LRR-based DNA segments.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] The functional dichotomy between two of the lymphocyte subsets parallels Ig and TCR molecules.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Immunity can be acquired either actively or passively.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Immunity is acquired actively when a person is exposed to foreign substances and the immune system responds.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Passive immunity is when antibodies are transferred from one host to another.
[src:immune-response/adaptive-immune-response] Both actively acquired and passively acquired immunity can be obtained by natural or artificial means.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] An **allergy** is an exaggerated immune response where the body mistakenly identifies an ordinarily harmless allergen as a threat.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergic reactions give rise to **allergic diseases** such as hay fever, allergic conjunctivitis, allergic asthma, atopic dermatitis, food allergies, and anaphylaxis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Symptoms of allergic diseases may include red eyes, an itchy rash, sneezing, coughing, a runny nose, shortness of breath, or swelling.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Common allergens include pollen, certain foods, metals, insect stings, medications, and materials, such as latex.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The development of allergies is due to genetic and environmental factors.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The mechanism of allergic reactions involves immunoglobulin E antibodies (IgE) binding to an allergen and then to a receptor on mast cells or basophils, where they trigger the release of inflammatory chemicals such as histamine.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Diagnosis is typically based on a person's medical history.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Further testing of the skin or blood may be useful in certain cases.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Positive tests, however, may not necessarily mean there is a significant allergy to the substance in question.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Early exposure of children to potential allergens may be protective.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Treatments for allergies include avoidance of known allergens and the use of medications such as steroids and antihistamines.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In severe reactions, injectable adrenaline (epinephrine) is recommended.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergen immunotherapy, which gradually exposes people to larger and larger amounts of allergen, is useful for some types of allergies such as hay fever and reactions to insect bites.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In the developed world, about 20% of people are affected by allergic rhinitis, food allergy affects 10% of adults and 8% of children, and about 20% have or have had atopic dermatitis at some point in time.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Depending on the country, about 1–18% of people have asthma.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Anaphylaxis occurs in between 0.05–2% of people.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Rates of many allergic diseases appear to be increasing.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The word "allergy" was first used by Clemens von Pirquet in 1906.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Many allergens, such as dust or pollen, are airborne particles.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In these cases, symptoms arise in areas exposed to air, such as the eyes, nose, and lungs.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] For instance, allergic rhinitis, also known as hay fever, irritates the nose, sneezing, itching, and redness of the eyes.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Inhaled allergens can also lead to increased production of mucus in the lungs, shortness of breath, coughing, and wheezing.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergic rhinitis can simultaneously occur with other allergic responses such as asthma.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Aside from these ambient allergens, allergic reactions can result from foods, insect stings, and reactions to medications like aspirin and antibiotics such as penicillin.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Symptoms of food allergy include abdominal pain, bloating, vomiting, diarrhea, itchy skin, and hives.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Food allergies rarely cause respiratory (asthmatic) reactions, or rhinitis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Insect stings, food, antibiotics, and certain medicines may produce a systemic allergic response that is also called anaphylaxis; multiple organ systems can be affected, including the digestive system, the respiratory system, and the circulatory system.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Depending on the severity, anaphylaxis can include skin reactions, bronchoconstriction, swelling, low blood pressure, coma, and death.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This type of reaction can be triggered suddenly or have a delayed onset.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The anaphylactic reaction may seem to subside, but may recur over time.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Substances that come into contact with the skin, such as latex, are also common causes of allergic reactions, known as contact dermatitis or eczema.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Skin allergies frequently cause rashes, or swelling and inflammation within the skin, in what is known as a "wheal and flare" reaction characteristic of hives and angioedema.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] With insect stings, a large local reaction may occur as an area of skin redness greater than 10 cm in size that can last one to two days.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This reaction may also occur after immunotherapy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The skin forms an effective barrier to the entry of most allergens, but this barrier cannot withstand everything.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] For example, an insect sting can breach the barrier and inject allergen into the affected spot.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] When an allergen enters the epidermis or dermis, it triggers a localized allergic reaction which activates the mast cells in the skin resulting in an immediate increase in permeability of blood vessels, leading to fluid leakage and swelling in the affected area.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Mast-cell activation also stimulates a skin lesion called the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Then the release of chemicals from local nerve endings by a nerve axon reflex causes the widening of surrounding cutaneous blood vessels, which causes redness of the surrounding skin.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] As part of the allergic response, the body has developed a secondary response that, in some individuals, causes a more widespread and sustained skin swelling.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This usually occurs about 8 hours after the allergen originally comes in contact with the skin.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] When an allergen is ingested, a dispersed form of wheal-and-flare reaction, known as urticaria or hives, will appear when the allergen enters the bloodstream and eventually reaches the skin.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This same skin reactivity allows allergists to test for existing allergies by injecting a small amount of an allergen into the skin, which causes a reaction at the injection site.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Even though these injections are very small and local, they still pose the risk of causing systemic anaphylaxis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Substances that come into contact with the airways may trigger allergic reactions in the nose, sinuses, throat and lungs.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergic rhinitis, often referred to as hay fever, is one of the most common airway allergies and is characterized by sneezing, nasal congestion, rhinorrhea and itching of the nose and eyes.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Airborne allergens commonly associated with allergic rhinitis include pollen, house dust mites, animal dander and mold spores.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergic reactions involving the lower airways may contribute to allergic asthma, in which exposure to allergens can lead to bronchoconstriction, wheezing, coughing and shortness of breath.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Common triggers include pollen, dust mites, animal allergens and occupational exposures such as flour dust or chemical sensitizers.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Some allergic airway reactions may occur rapidly after exposure, while others develop over several hours.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Severe reactions involving airway swelling may impair breathing and constitute a medical emergency.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) is responsible for distinguishing pathogenic organisms from harmless food proteins and commensal bacteria.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Antigens sampled across the intestinal epithelium are presented by CD103+ dendritic cells, which migrate to mesenteric lymph nodes and promote differentiation of Foxp3+ regulatory T cells (Tregs).
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] These Tregs subsequently return to the intestinal lamina propria, where cytokines such as interleukin-10 and transforming growth factor-β (TGF-β) contribute to the maintenance of immune tolerance and suppression of allergic T helper 2 (Th2) responses.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Disruption of these regulatory pathways may contribute to allergic sensitization and the development of food allergy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Impairment of the intestinal epithelial barrier, altered antigen processing, inflammation, or reduced regulatory T-cell activity may shift immune responses toward IgE-mediated hypersensitivity.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Such defects in oral tolerance have been associated with increased Th2 polarization, elevated allergen-specific IgE production, and reduced regulatory immune activity.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Environmental and dietary factors, including vitamin D deficiency, infections, antibiotic exposure, and changes in food processing, may also influence allergy development through their effects on gut immunity and epithelial integrity.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The intestinal microbiome is increasingly recognized as an important factor in allergy development.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Early-life alterations in the composition and diversity of the intestinal microbiota have been associated with an increased risk of food allergy and atopic disease.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Commensal bacteria contribute to immune maturation, maintenance of epithelial barrier function, and induction of tolerogenic immune responses.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Reduced microbial diversity and loss of certain bacterial taxa may impair oral tolerance and promote allergic sensitization.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Short-chain fatty acids produced by intestinal bacteria may further support regulatory immune pathways and intestinal barrier integrity.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Sensitization to food allergens may also occur through non-oral routes.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Exposure to allergens through damaged skin, particularly in individuals with impaired skin barriers such as those with atopic dermatitis, may predispose to food allergy if oral tolerance has not yet been established.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This has contributed to the hypothesis that the timing, route, and context of allergen exposure influence whether tolerance or allergic sensitization develops.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Research into gastrointestinal immune mechanisms has influenced preventive approaches to food allergy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Early introduction of allergenic foods, including peanuts and eggs, during infancy has been associated in some populations with a reduced risk of food allergy, likely by promoting oral tolerance during critical periods of immune development.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Risk factors for allergies can be placed in two broad categories: host and environmental factors.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Host factors include heredity, sex, race, and age, with heredity being by far the most significant.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] However, there has been a recent increase in the incidence of allergic disorders that cannot be explained by genetic factors alone.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Four major environmental candidates are alterations in exposure to infectious diseases during early childhood, environmental pollution, allergen levels, and dietary changes.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Dust mite allergy, also known as house dust allergy, is a sensitization and allergic reaction to the droppings of house dust mites.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The allergy is common and can trigger allergic reactions such as asthma, eczema, or itching.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The mite's gut contains potent digestive enzymes (notably peptidase 1) that persist in their faeces and are major inducers of allergic reactions such as wheezing.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The mite's exoskeleton can also contribute to allergic reactions.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Unlike scabies mites or skin follicle mites, house dust mites do not burrow under the skin and are not parasitic.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Dust mite-proof encasements to mattress, pillow, and duvet prevent chronic contact with allergens.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] A wide variety of foods can cause allergic reactions, but 90% of allergic responses to foods are caused by cow's milk, soy, eggs, wheat, peanuts, tree nuts, fish, and shellfish.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Other food allergies, affecting less than 1 person per 10,000 population, may be considered "rare".
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The most common food allergy in the US population is a sensitivity to crustacea.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Although peanut allergies are notorious for their severity, peanut allergies are not the most common food allergy in adults or children.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Other allergens may trigger severe or life-threatening reactions and are more common when combined with asthma.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Rates of allergies differ between adults and children.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Children can sometimes outgrow peanut allergies.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Egg allergies affect one to two percent of children but are outgrown by about two-thirds of children by the age of 5.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The sensitivity is usually to proteins in the white, rather than the yolk.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Milk-protein allergies—distinct from lactose intolerance—are most common in children.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Approximately 60% of milk-protein reactions are immunoglobulin E–mediated, with the remaining usually attributable to inflammation of the colon.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Some people are unable to tolerate milk from goats or sheep as well as from cows, and many are also unable to tolerate dairy products such as cheese.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Roughly 10% of children with a milk allergy will have a reaction to beef.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Lactose intolerance, a common reaction to milk, is not a form of allergy at all, but due to the absence of an enzyme in the digestive tract.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Those with tree nut allergies may be allergic to one or many tree nuts, including pecans, pistachios, and walnuts.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In addition, seeds, including sesame seeds and poppy seeds, contain oils in which protein is present, which may elicit an allergic reaction.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergens can be transferred from one food to another through genetic engineering; however, genetic modification can also remove allergens.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Little research has been done on the natural variation of allergen concentrations in unmodified crops.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Latex can trigger an IgE-mediated cutaneous, respiratory, and systemic reaction.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The prevalence of latex allergy in the general population is believed to be less than one percent.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In a hospital study, 1 in 800 surgical patients (0.125 percent) reported latex sensitivity, although the sensitivity among healthcare workers is higher, between seven and ten percent.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Researchers attribute this higher level to the exposure of healthcare workers to areas with significant airborne latex allergens, such as operating rooms, intensive-care units, and dental suites.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] These latex-rich environments may sensitize healthcare workers who regularly inhale allergenic proteins.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The most prevalent response to latex is allergic contact dermatitis, a delayed hypersensitivity reaction that manifests as dry, crusted lesions.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This reaction usually lasts 48–96 hours.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Sweating or rubbing the area under the glove aggravates the lesions, possibly leading to ulcerations.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Anaphylactic reactions occur most often in sensitive patients who have been exposed to a surgeon's latex gloves during abdominal surgery, but other mucosal exposures, such as dental procedures, can also produce systemic reactions.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Latex and banana sensitivity may cross-react.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Furthermore, those with latex allergy may also have sensitivities to avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] These people often have perioral itching and local urticaria.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Only occasionally have these food-induced allergies induced systemic responses.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Researchers suspect that the cross-reactivity of latex with banana, avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut occurs because latex proteins are structurally homologous with some other plant proteins.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] About 10% of people report that they are allergic to penicillin; however, of that 10%, 90% turn out not to be.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Serious allergies only occur in about 0.03%.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] One of the main sources of human allergies is insects.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Insect bites, stings, ingestion, and inhalation can trigger an insect allergy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Another non-food protein reaction, urushiol-induced contact dermatitis, originates after contact with poison ivy, eastern poison oak, western poison oak, or poison sumac.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Urushiol, which is not itself a protein, acts as a hapten and chemically reacts with, binds to, and changes the shape of integral membrane proteins on exposed skin cells.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The immune system does not recognize the affected cells as normal parts of the body, causing a T-cell-mediated immune response.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Of these poisonous plants, sumac is the most virulent.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The resulting dermatological response to the reaction between urushiol and membrane proteins includes redness, swelling, papules, vesicles, blisters, and streaking.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Estimates vary on the fraction of the population that will have an immune system response.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Approximately 25% of the population will have a strong allergic response to urushiol.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In general, approximately 80–90% of adults will develop a rash if they are exposed to 0.0050 mg (7.7×10−5 gr) of purified urushiol.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Some people are so sensitive that a molecular trace on the skin can initiate an allergic reaction.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergic diseases are strongly familial; identical twins are likely to have the same allergic diseases about 70% of the time; the same allergy occurs about 40% of the time in non-identical twins.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergic parents are more likely to have allergic children and those children's allergies are likely to be more severe than those in children of non-allergic parents.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Some allergies, however, are not consistent along genealogies; parents who are allergic to peanuts may have children who are allergic to ragweed.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The likelihood of developing allergies is inherited and related to an irregularity in the immune system, but the specific allergen is not.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The risk of allergic sensitization and the development of allergies varies with age, with young children most at risk.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Several studies have shown that IgE levels are highest in childhood and fall rapidly between the ages of 10 and 30 years.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The peak prevalence of hay fever is highest in children and young adults, and the incidence of asthma is highest in children under 10.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Ethnicity may play a role in some allergies; however, racial factors have been difficult to separate from environmental influences and changes due to migration.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] It has been suggested that different genetic loci are responsible for asthma, to be specific, in people of European, Hispanic, Asian, and African origins.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Some loci, such as PRDM2 and POU2AF1, showed pleiotropic effects linking allergic and autoimmune conditions, suggesting shared inflammatory pathways across epithelial tissues.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Within atopic airway disease specifically, the same review noted that IL-13—produced mainly by activated TH2 cells—is a key driver of eosinophilic airway inflammation and remodeling, acting partly through pathways independent of IgE and eosinophils.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergic diseases are caused by inappropriate immunological responses to harmless antigens driven by a TH2-mediated immune response.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Many bacteria and viruses elicit a TH1-mediated immune response, which down-regulates TH2 responses.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The first proposed mechanism of action of the hygiene hypothesis was that insufficient stimulation of the TH1 arm of the immune system leads to an overactive TH2 arm, which in turn leads to allergic disease.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In other words, individuals living in too sterile an environment are not exposed to enough pathogens to keep the immune system busy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Since our bodies evolved to deal with a certain level of such pathogens, when they are not exposed to this level, the immune system will attack harmless antigens.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Thus, normally benign microbial objects—like pollen—will trigger an immune response.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] It is used to explain the increase in allergic diseases that have been seen since industrialization, and the higher incidence of allergic diseases in more developed countries.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The hygiene hypothesis has now expanded to include exposure to symbiotic bacteria and parasites as important modulators of immune system development, along with infectious agents.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Epidemiological data support the hygiene hypothesis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Longitudinal studies in the third world demonstrate an increase in immunological disorders as a country grows more affluent and, it is presumed, cleaner.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The use of antibiotics in the first year of life has been linked to asthma and other allergic diseases.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The use of antibacterial cleaning products has also been associated with a higher incidence of asthma, as has birth by caesarean section rather than vaginal birth.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Chronic stress can aggravate allergic conditions.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This has been attributed to a T helper 2 (TH2)-predominant response driven by suppression of interleukin 12 by both the autonomic nervous system and the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Stress management in highly susceptible individuals may improve symptoms.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergic diseases are more common in industrialized countries than in countries that are more traditional or agricultural, and there is a higher rate of allergic disease in urban populations versus rural populations, although these differences are becoming less defined.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Historically, the trees planted in urban areas were predominantly male to prevent litter from seeds and fruits, but the high ratio of male trees causes high pollen counts, a phenomenon that horticulturist Tom Ogren has called "botanical sexism".
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Alterations in exposure to microorganisms is another plausible explanation, at present, for the increase in atopic allergy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Endotoxin exposure reduces release of inflammatory cytokines such as TNF-α, IFNγ, interleukin-10, and interleukin-12 from white blood cells (leukocytes) that circulate in the blood.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Certain microbe-sensing proteins, known as Toll-like receptors, found on the surface of cells in the body, are also thought to be involved in these processes.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Parasitic worms and similar parasites are present in untreated drinking water in developing countries, and were present in the water of developed countries until the routine chlorination and purification of drinking water supplies.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Recent research has shown that some common parasites, such as intestinal worms (e.g., hookworms), secrete chemicals into the gut wall (and, hence, the bloodstream) that suppress the immune system and prevent the body from attacking the parasite.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This gives rise to a new slant on the hygiene hypothesis theory—that co-evolution of humans and parasites has led to an immune system that functions correctly only in the presence of the parasites.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Without them, the immune system becomes unbalanced and oversensitive.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In particular, research suggests that allergies may coincide with the delayed establishment of gut flora in infants.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] However, the research to support this theory is conflicting, with some studies performed in China and Ethiopia showing an increase in allergy in people infected with intestinal worms.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Clinical trials have been initiated to test the effectiveness of helminthic therapy with certain worms in treating some allergies.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] It may be that the term 'parasite' could turn out to be inappropriate, and in fact a hitherto unsuspected symbiosis is at work.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] These TH2 cells interact with other lymphocytes called B cells, whose role is the production of antibodies.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Coupled with signals provided by IL-4, this interaction stimulates the B cell to begin production of a large amount of a particular type of antibody known as IgE.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Secreted IgE circulates in the blood and binds to an IgE-specific receptor (a kind of Fc receptor called FcεRI) on the surface of other kinds of immune cells called mast cells and basophils, which are both involved in the acute inflammatory response.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] At this stage, the IgE-coated cells are sensitized to the allergen.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] If later exposure to the same allergen occurs, the allergen can bind to IgE molecules held on the surface of the mast cells or basophils.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Cross-linking of the IgE and Fc receptors occurs when more than one IgE-receptor complex interacts with the same allergenic molecule and activates the sensitized cell.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This results in rhinorrhea, itchiness, dyspnea, and anaphylaxis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Depending on the individual, allergen, and mode of introduction, the symptoms can be system-wide (classical anaphylaxis) or localized to specific body systems.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Asthma is localized to the respiratory system, and eczema is localized to the dermis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] After the chemical mediators of the acute response subside, late-phase responses can often occur.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This is due to the migration of other leukocytes such as neutrophils, lymphocytes, eosinophils, and macrophages to the initial site.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The reaction is usually seen 2–24 hours after the original reaction.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Cytokines from mast cells may play a role in the persistence of long-term effects.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Late-phase responses in asthma differ slightly from those seen in other allergic responses.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] They are still caused by the release of mediators from eosinophils and remain dependent on TH2 cell activity.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Although allergic contact dermatitis is termed an "allergic" reaction (which usually refers to type I hypersensitivity), its pathophysiology involves a reaction that more correctly corresponds to a type IV hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In type IV hypersensitivity, there is activation of certain types of T cells (CD8+) that destroy target cells on contact, as well as activated macrophages that produce hydrolytic enzymes.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Effective management of allergic diseases relies on the ability to make an accurate diagnosis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergy testing can help confirm or rule out allergies.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Correct diagnosis, counseling, and avoidance advice based on valid allergy test results reduce the incidence of symptoms and need for medications, and improve quality of life.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] To assess the presence of allergen-specific IgE antibodies, two different methods can be used: a skin prick test or an allergy blood test.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Both methods are recommended, and they have similar diagnostic value.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Skin prick tests and blood tests are equally cost-effective, and health economic evidence shows that both tests are cost-effective compared with no test.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Early and more accurate diagnoses save costs due to reduced consultations, referrals to secondary care, misdiagnosis, and emergency admissions.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergy undergoes dynamic changes over time.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Regular allergy testing of relevant allergens provides information on if and how patient management can be changed to improve health and quality of life.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Annual testing is often the practice for determining whether allergy to milk, egg, soy, and wheat have been outgrown, and the testing interval is extended to 2–3 years for allergy to peanut, tree nuts, fish, and crustacean shellfish.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Results of follow-up testing can guide decision-making regarding whether and when it is safe to introduce or re-introduce allergenic food into the diet.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Skin testing is also known as "puncture testing" and "prick testing" since it involves a series of tiny punctures or pricks being placed into the patient's skin.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Tiny amounts of suspected allergens and/or their extracts (*e.g.*, pollen, grass, mite proteins, peanut extract) are introduced to sites on the skin marked with pen or dye (the ink/dye should be carefully selected, lest it cause an allergic response itself).
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] A negative and positive control are also included for comparison (e.g., negative is saline or glycerin; positive is histamine).
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] A small plastic or metal device is used to puncture or prick the skin.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Sometimes, allergens are injected "intradermally" into the patient's skin, with a needle and syringe.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Common areas for testing include the inside of the forearm and the back.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] If the patient is allergic to the substance, then a visible inflammatory reaction will usually occur within 30 minutes.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] This response ranges from slight reddening of the skin to a full-blown hive (called "wheal and flare") in more sensitive patients, similar to a mosquito bite.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Interpretation of the results of the skin prick test is usually done by allergists on a severity scale, with +/− meaning borderline reactivity, and 4+ representing a large reaction.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Increasingly, allergists are measuring and recording the diameter of the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Interpretation by well-trained allergists is often guided by relevant literature.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In general, a positive response is interpreted when the wheal of an antigen is ≥3 mm larger than the wheal of the negative control (e.g., saline or glycerin).
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Some patients may believe they have determined their own allergic sensitivity from observation.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] A skin test is much better than patient observation for allergy detection.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] If a serious life-threatening anaphylactic reaction has brought a patient in for evaluation, some allergists may prefer to perform an initial blood test before conducting a skin prick test.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Skin testing may also not be possible in patients with widespread skin disease or those who have taken antihistamine within the past several days.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Patch testing is a diagnostic method used to identify substances that cause allergic contact dermatitis through a delayed hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] During the procedure, small amounts of potential allergens are applied to the skin, usually on the back, using adhesive patches containing standardized allergen preparations.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The patches are typically left in place for 48 hours, after which the skin is examined for localized eczematous reactions.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Additional readings are commonly performed 72–96 hours after application because allergic contact reactions may develop slowly.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Unlike skin prick testing, which is used to diagnose immediate IgE-mediated allergies, patch testing evaluates delayed type IV hypersensitivity reactions mediated by T cells.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergy blood testing, typically measuring allergen-specific IgE, is a quick test that can be ordered by a qualified healthcare professional.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Unlike skin-prick testing, it is not affected by antihistamines and may be used when skin testing is impractical, such as in people with extensive eczema or other skin disease, in pregnancy, or when there is concern about provoking symptoms.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] It can be performed in adults and children, including infants, although results must be interpreted together with the clinical history because sensitisation does not always mean clinical allergy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] An allergy blood test is available through most laboratories.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] A sample of the patient's blood is sent to a laboratory for analysis, and the results are sent back a few days later.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Multiple allergens can be detected with a single blood sample.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergy blood tests are very safe because the person is not exposed to any allergens during the testing procedure.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] After the onset of anaphylaxis or a severe allergic reaction, guidelines recommend that emergency departments obtain a time-sensitive blood test to measure tryptase levels and assess for mast cells activation.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The test measures the concentration of specific IgE antibodies in the blood.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Quantitative IgE test results increase the possibility of ranking how different substances may affect symptoms.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] A rule of thumb is that the higher the IgE antibody value, the greater the likelihood of symptoms.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergens found at low levels that today do not result in symptoms cannot predict future symptom development.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The quantitative allergy blood result can help determine what a patient is allergic to, predict and monitor disease progression, estimate the risk of a severe reaction, and explain cross-reactivity.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] A low total IgE level is not adequate to rule out sensitization to commonly inhaled allergens.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Statistical methods, such as ROC curves, predictive value calculations, and likelihood ratios have been used to examine the relationship of various testing methods to each other.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] These methods have shown that patients with high total IgE have a high probability of allergic sensitization, but further investigation with allergy tests for specific IgE antibodies for a carefully chosen set of allergens is often warranted.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Laboratory methods to measure specific IgE antibodies for allergy testing include enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay, radioallergosorbent test, fluorescent enzyme immunoassay, and chemiluminescence immunoassay.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Before a diagnosis of allergic disease can be confirmed, other plausible causes of the presenting symptoms must be considered.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Vasomotor rhinitis, for example, is one of many illnesses that share symptoms with allergic rhinitis, underscoring the need for professional differential diagnosis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Once a diagnosis of asthma, rhinitis, anaphylaxis, or other allergic disease has been made, there are several methods for discovering the causative agent of that allergy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Giving peanut products early in childhood may decrease the risk of allergies, and only breastfeeding during at least the first few months of life may decrease the risk of allergic dermatitis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] There is little evidence that a mother's diet during pregnancy or breastfeeding affects the risk of allergies, although there has been some research to show that irregular cow's milk exposure might increase the risk of cow's milk allergy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] There is some evidence that delayed introduction of certain foods is useful, and that early exposure to potential allergens may actually be protective.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Following revisions to US and UK pediatric guidelines in 2015 and 2017 that encouraged introducing peanut products to high-risk infants at four to six months of age, one 2025 analysis found a 43% drop in the frequency of peanut allergies, with an estimated 40,000 cases prevented.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] According to that report, some pediatric experts have cautioned that real-world implementation of the guidelines may be inconsistent.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Fish oil supplementation during pregnancy is associated with a lower risk of food sensitivities.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Probiotic supplements during pregnancy or infancy may help to prevent atopic dermatitis.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Management of allergies typically involves avoiding the allergy trigger and taking medications to relieve symptoms.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergen immunotherapy may be useful for some types of allergies.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Several medications may be used to block the actions of allergic mediators, prevent cell activation, and degranulation processes.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] These include antihistamines, glucocorticoids, epinephrine (adrenaline), mast cell stabilizers, and antileukotriene agents are common treatments of allergic diseases.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Anticholinergics, decongestants, and other compounds thought to impair eosinophil chemotaxis are also commonly used.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Although rare, the severity of anaphylaxis often requires epinephrine injection, and where medical care is unavailable, a device known as an epinephrine autoinjector may be used.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Allergen immunotherapy is useful for environmental allergies, allergies to insect bites, and asthma.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Its benefit for food allergies is unclear and thus not recommended.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Immunotherapy involves exposing people to larger and larger amounts of allergen in an effort to change the immune system's response.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Meta-analyses have found that injections of allergens under the skin is effective in the treatment in allergic rhinitis in children and in asthma.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The benefits may last for years after treatment is stopped.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] It is generally safe and effective for allergic rhinitis and conjunctivitis, allergic forms of asthma, and stinging insects.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] To a lesser extent, the evidence also supports the use of sublingual immunotherapy for rhinitis and asthma.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] For seasonal allergies the benefit is small.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In this form the allergen is given under the tongue and people often prefer it to injections.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Immunotherapy is not recommended as a stand-alone treatment for asthma.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] An experimental treatment, enzyme potentiated desensitization (EPD), has been tried for decades but is not generally accepted as effective.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] EPD uses dilutions of allergen and an enzyme, beta-glucuronidase, to which T-regulatory lymphocytes are supposed to respond by favoring desensitization, or down-regulation, rather than sensitization.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] EPD has also been tried for the treatment of autoimmune diseases, but evidence does not show effectiveness.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] A review found no effectiveness of homeopathic treatments and no difference compared with placebo.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The authors concluded that, based on rigorous clinical trials of all types of homeopathy for childhood and adolescent ailments, there is no convincing evidence that supports the use of homeopathic treatments.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The allergic diseases—hay fever and asthma—have increased in the Western world over the past 2–3 decades.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Increases in allergic asthma and other atopic disorders in industrialized nations, it is estimated, began in the 1960s and 1970s, with further increases occurring during the 1980s and 1990s, although some suggest that a steady rise in sensitization has been occurring since the 1920s.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The number of new cases per year of atopy in developing countries has, in general, remained much lower.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Although genetic factors govern susceptibility to atopic disease, increases in atopy have occurred within too short a period to be explained by a genetic change in the population, thus pointing to environmental or lifestyle changes.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Several hypotheses have been identified to explain this increased rate.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Increased exposure to perennial allergens may be due to housing changes and increased time spent indoors, and changes in cleanliness may decrease activation of a common immune control mechanisms or hygiene, and exacerbated by dietary changes, obesity, and decline in physical exercise.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The hygiene hypothesis maintains that high living standards and hygienic conditions expose children to fewer infections.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] It is thought that reduced bacterial and viral infections early in life direct the maturing immune system away from TH1 type responses, leading to unrestrained TH2 responses that allow for an increase in allergy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Changes in rates and types of infection alone, however, have been unable to explain the observed increase in allergic disease, and recent evidence has focused attention on the importance of the gastrointestinal microbial environment.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] It is speculated that these infections exert their effect by critically altering TH1/TH2 regulation.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Important elements of newer hygiene hypotheses also include exposure to endotoxins, exposure to pets and growing up on a farm.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Some symptoms attributable to allergic diseases are mentioned in ancient sources.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Particularly, three members of the Roman Julio-Claudian dynasty (Augustus, Claudius and Britannicus) are suspected to have a family history of atopy.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The concept of "allergy" was originally introduced in 1906 by the Viennese pediatrician Clemens von Pirquet, after he noticed that patients who had received injections of horse serum or smallpox vaccine usually had quicker, more severe reactions to second injections.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Pirquet called this phenomenon "allergy" from the Ancient Greek words ἄλλος *allos* meaning "other" and ἔργον *ergon* meaning "work".
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] All forms of hypersensitivity were previously classified as allergies, and all were thought to be caused by an improper activation of the immune system.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Later, it became clear that several disease mechanisms were implicated, with a common link to disordered immune system activation.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In 1963, a new classification scheme was designed by Philip Gell and Robin Coombs that described four types of hypersensitivity reactions, known as Type I to Type IV hypersensitivity.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] With this new classification, the word *allergy*, sometimes clarified as a *true allergy*, was restricted to type I hypersensitivities (also called immediate hypersensitivity), which are characterized as rapidly developing reactions involving IgE antibodies.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] A breakthrough in understanding the mechanisms of allergy was the discovery of the antibody class labeled immunoglobulin E (IgE).
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] IgE was simultaneously discovered in 1966–67 by two independent groups: Ishizaka's team at the Children's Asthma Research Institute and Hospital in Denver, USA, and by Gunnar Johansson and Hans Bennich in Uppsala, Sweden.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Their joint paper was published in April 1969.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] Radiometric assays include the radioallergosorbent test (RAST test) method, which uses IgE-binding (anti-IgE) antibodies labeled with radioactive isotopes for quantifying the levels of IgE antibody in the blood.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The RAST methodology was invented and marketed in 1974 by Pharmacia Diagnostics AB, Uppsala, Sweden, and the acronym RAST is actually a brand name.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] In 1989, Pharmacia Diagnostics AB replaced it with a superior test named the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, which uses the newer fluorescence-labeled technology.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p01] The updated version, the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, is the only specific IgE assay the Food and Drug Administration has approved to quantitatively report to its detection limit of 0.1 kU/L.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] The medical speciality that studies, diagnoses, and treats diseases caused by allergies is called allergology.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] An allergist is a physician specially trained to manage and treat allergies, asthma, and other allergic diseases.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] Becoming an allergist/immunologist requires completion of at least nine years of training.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] After completing medical school and graduating with a medical degree, a physician will undergo three years of training in internal medicine (to become an internist) or pediatrics (to become a pediatrician).
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] Internists or pediatricians wishing to focus on the sub-specialty of allergy-immunology then complete at least an additional two years of study, called a fellowship, in an allergy/immunology training program.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] Allergists/immunologists listed as ABAI-certified have successfully passed the certifying ABAI examination following their fellowship.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] In the United Kingdom, allergy is a subspecialty of general medicine or pediatrics.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] After obtaining postgraduate exams (MRCP or MRCPCH), a doctor works for several years as a specialist registrar before qualifying for the General Medical Council specialist register.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] Allergy services may also be delivered by immunologists.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] A 2003 Royal College of Physicians report presented a case for improvement of what were felt to be inadequate allergy services in the UK.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] In 2006, the House of Lords convened a subcommittee.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] It concluded likewise in 2007 that allergy services were insufficient to deal with what the Lords referred to as an "allergy epidemic" and its social cost; it made several recommendations.
[src:immune-response/allergy-p02] Low-allergen foods are being developed, as are improvements in skin prick test predictions; evaluation of the atopy patch test, wasp sting outcomes predictions, a rapidly disintegrating epinephrine tablet, and anti-IL-5 for eosinophilic diseases.
[src:immune-response/anergic] In immunology, **anergy** characterizes the absence of a response from the body's defense mechanisms when confronted with foreign substances.
[src:immune-response/anergic] This phenomenon involves the direct induction of peripheral lymphocyte tolerance.
[src:immune-response/anergic] When an individual is in a state of anergy, it signifies that their immune system is incapable of mounting a typical response against a specific antigen, typically a self-antigen.
[src:immune-response/anergic] The term anergy specifically refers to lymphocytes that exhibit an inability to react to their designated antigen.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Notably, anergy constitutes one of the essential processes fostering tolerance within the immune system, alongside clonal deletion and immunoregulation.
[src:immune-response/anergic] These processes collectively act to modify the immune response, preventing the inadvertent self-destruction that could result from an overactive immune system.
[src:immune-response/anergic] This phenomenon was first described in B lymphocytes by Gustav Nossal and termed "**clonal anergy**." The clones of B lymphocytes in this case can still be found alive in the circulation, but are ineffective at mounting immune responses.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Later Ronald Schwartz and Marc Jenkins described a similar process operating in the T lymphocyte.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Many viruses (HIV being the most extreme example) seem to exploit the immune system's use of tolerance induction to evade the immune system, though the suppression of specific antigens is done by fewer pathogens (notably *Mycobacterium leprae*).
[src:immune-response/anergic] At the cellular level, "anergy" is the inability of an immune cell to mount a complete response against its target.
[src:immune-response/anergic] In the immune system, circulating cells called lymphocytes form a primary army that defends the body against pathogenic viruses, bacteria and parasites.
[src:immune-response/anergic] There are two major kinds of lymphocytes – the T lymphocyte and the B lymphocyte.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Among the millions of lymphocytes in the human body, only a few actually are specific for any particular infectious agent.
[src:immune-response/anergic] At the time of infection, these few cells must be recruited and allowed to multiply rapidly.
[src:immune-response/anergic] This process – called "clonal expansion" – allows the body to quickly mobilise an army of clones, as and when required.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Such immune response is anticipatory and its specificity is assured by pre-existing clones of lymphocytes, which expand in response to specific antigen (process called "clonal selection").
[src:immune-response/anergic] This specific clonal army then combats the pathogen until the body is free of the infection.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Following clearance of the infection, the clones that are no longer needed die away naturally.
[src:immune-response/anergic] However, a small number of the body's army of lymphocytes are able to react with proteins that are normally present in a healthy body.
[src:immune-response/anergic] The clonal expansion of those cells can lead to autoimmune diseases, wherein the body attacks itself.
[src:immune-response/anergic] In order to prevent this process, lymphocytes possess an intrinsic quality-control mechanism.
[src:immune-response/anergic] This machinery shuts down the lymphocytes' ability to expand, if the trigger for the expansion turns out to be the body's own protein.
[src:immune-response/anergic] T-cell anergy can arise when the T-cell does not receive appropriate co-stimulation in the presence of specific antigen recognition.
[src:immune-response/anergic] B-cell anergy can be induced by exposure to soluble circulating antigen, and is often marked by a downregulation of surface IgM expression and partial blockade of intracellular signaling pathways.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Understanding the molecular mechanism of anergy induction in T lymphocytes unveils the intricate interplay of signaling pathways governing immune responses.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Upon stimulation, the T cell receptor (TCR) in conjunction with co-stimulatory receptors orchestrates a comprehensive activation of all the T-cell’s signaling pathways, collectively termed full T-cell stimulation.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Among these pathways, the calcium-dependent arm of lymphocyte signaling is particularly pivotal, triggered by TCR engagement.
[src:immune-response/anergic] This initiates a cascade culminating in an elevation of intracellular Ca+II concentration, a critical event in T cell activation.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Under such conditions, the calcium-dependent phosphatase calcineurin acts on the transcription factor NFAT, facilitating its translocation to the nucleus, where it regulates gene expression.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Expanding upon this complexity, during full T-cell stimulation the co-stimulatory receptor CD28 activates PI3K and other pathways, augmenting the nuclear levels of key transcription factors such as rel, NF-κB and AP-1 beyond those induced by TCR activation alone.
[src:immune-response/anergic] The formation of AP-1, fos/jun heterodimer, further complexes with NFAT, creating a transcriptional complex crucial for the expression of genes associated with T-cell productive responses, including IL-2 and its receptor.
[src:immune-response/anergic] In contrast, TCR signaling in the absence of co-stimulatory receptors predominantly activates the calcium arm of the signaling pathway, leading to NFAT activation alone.
[src:immune-response/anergic] However, without the concurrent induction of AP-1 by other pathways, NFAT fails to form the transcriptional complex necessary for a productive T-cell response.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Instead, NFAT homodimerizes, functioning as a transcriptional factor that induces anergy in the lymphocyte.
[src:immune-response/anergic] NFAT homodimers play a direct role in the expression of anergy-associated genes, such as the ubiquitin ligase GRAIL and the protease caspase 3.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Furthermore, anergized cells exhibit decreased expression levels of IL-2, TNFα, and IFNγ, characteristic of a productive response, while favoring the production of the anti-inflammatory cytokine IL-10.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Although three NFAT proteins - NFAT1, NFAT2 and NFAT4 - are preset in T-cells, they demonstrate redundancy to some extent.
[src:immune-response/anergic] In the context of antigen presentation by antigen-presenting cells (APC), T lymphocytes undergo a productive response when the antigen is appropriately presented, activating T cell co-stimulatory receptors.
[src:immune-response/anergic] However, encountering antigens not presented by the APCs or weakly presented antigens induces anergic responses in T cells.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Notably, strong stimulation through IL-2 or TCR/co-stimulatory receptors can overcome anergy, highlighting the dynamic nature of immune regulation.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Moreover, recent research has illuminated the role of regulatory T cells (Tregs) in modulating T cell responses and maintaining immune tolerance.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Tregs, characterized by the expression of the transcription factor Foxp3, exert immunosuppressive effects by inhibiting the activation and function of effector T cells.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Importantly, Tregs can directly interact with anergic T cells, further reinforcing their state of unresponsiveness and promoting peripheral tolerance.
[src:immune-response/anergic] This interaction involves various mechanisms, including the secretion of inhibitory cytokines such as IL-10 and TGF-β, as well as cell-contact-dependent suppression mediated by molecules like CTLA-4.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Understanding the intricate crosstalk between Tregs and anergic T cells provides valuable insights into the maintenance of immune homeostasis and has implications for therapeutic strategies aimed at modulating immune responses in autoimmune diseases and transplantation.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Anergy may be taken advantage of for therapeutic uses.
[src:immune-response/anergic] The immune response to grafting of transplanted organs and tissues could be minimized without weakening the entire immune system— a side effect of immunosuppressive drugs like cyclosporine.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Anergy may also be used to induce activated lymphocytes to become unresponsive with autoimmune diseases like diabetes mellitus, multiple sclerosis and rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Likewise, preventing anergy in response to a tumoral growth may help in anti-tumor responses.
[src:immune-response/anergic] It might also be used for immunotherapeutic treatment of allergies.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Dominant and recessive tolerance are forms of a peripheral tolerance (the other tolerance beside peripheral is a central tolerance).
[src:immune-response/anergic] Where so called recessive tolerance is associated with anergized lymphocytes as described above, in the dominant form of tolerance, specialized T-reg cells which actively ablate the immune response are developed from the naive T lymphocyte.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Similarly to recessive tolerance, unopposed NFAT signalling is also important for T-reg induction.
[src:immune-response/anergic] In this case, the NFAT pathway activates another transcription factor – FOXP3 that is a marker of T-regs and participates in their genetic program.
[src:immune-response/anergic] The "Multitest Mérieux" or "CMI Multitest" system (Multitest IMC, Istituto Merieux Italia, Rome, Italy) has been used as a general test of the level of cellular immunity.
[src:immune-response/anergic] It is an intradermal test of skin reactivity (similar to tuberculin tests) in which a control (glycerol) is used with seven antigens of bacterial or fungal origin (tetanus toxoid, tuberculin, diphtheria, streptococcus, candida, trichophyton, and proteus).
[src:immune-response/anergic] In this test reactions are categorized according to the number of antigens provoking a response and the summed extent of the skin response to all seven antigens.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Here **anergy** is defined as a region of skin reactivity of 0–1 mm, **hypoergy** as a reaction of 2–9 mm in response to fewer than three antigens, **normergic** as a reaction of 10–39 mm or to three or more antigens, and **hyperergy** for a reaction of 40 mm or more.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Various chemicals inducing/inhibiting described T cell signalling pathways can be used to study the anergy.
[src:immune-response/anergic] The anergy in T cells can be induced by Ionomycin, the ionophore capable of raising intracellular concentration of calcium ions artificially.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Conversely, Ca+II chelators such as EGTA can sequester calcium ions making them unable to cause the anergy.
[src:immune-response/anergic] Blocking of the pathway leading to the anergy can be also done by cyclosporin A, which is capable of inhibiting calcineurin – the phosphatase responsible for dephosphorylating of NFAT priming its activation.
[src:immune-response/anergic] PMA, phorbol 12-myristate 13-acetate, along with ionomycin is used to induce full T cells activation by mimicking signals provided naturally by TCR/costimulatory receptors activation.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] An **antibody** (**Ab**), or **immunoglobulin** (**Ig**), is a large protein belonging to the immunoglobulin superfamily which is used by the immune system to identify and neutralize antigens such as those that exist on bacteria and virus cells, including those that cause disease.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Each individual antibody recognizes one or more specific antigens, and antigens (a portmanteau of "antibody generator") of virtually any size and chemical composition can be recognized.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Each of the branching chains comprising the "Y" of an antibody contains a paratope (the antigen-binding site) that specifically binds to one particular epitope (a specific part of an antigen bound by the paratope) on an antigen, allowing the two molecules to bind together with precision.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Using this mechanism, antibodies can effectively "tag" the antigen (or a microbe or an infected cell bearing such an antigen) for attack by cells of the immune system, or can neutralize it directly (for example, by blocking a part of a virus that is essential for its ability to invade a host cell).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies may be borne on the surface of an immune cell, as in a B cell receptor, or they may exist freely by being secreted into the extracellular space.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The term *antibody* generally refers to the free (secreted) form, while the term *immunoglobulin* can refer to either forms.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Since they are, broadly speaking, the same protein, the terms are often treated as synonymous.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] To allow the immune system to recognize millions of different antigens, the antigen-binding paratopes at each tip of the antibody come in an equally wide variety.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The rest of an antibody's structure is much less variable; in humans, antibodies occur in five classes or isotypes: IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Human IgG and IgA antibodies are also divided into discrete subclasses (IgG1, IgG2, IgG3, and IgG4; IgA1 and IgA2).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The class refers to the functions triggered by the antibody (also known as effector functions), in addition to some other structural features.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies from different classes also differ in where they are released in the body and at what stage of an immune response.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Between species, while classes and subclasses of antibodies may be shared (at least in name), their function and distribution throughout the body may be different, which complicates the use of animal models in studying antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] For example, mouse IgG1 is closer to human IgG2 than to human IgG1 in terms of its function.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In general, antibodies are considered part of the adaptive immune system, though this classification can become complicated.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] For example, natural IgM, which are made by B-1 cells that have properties more similar to innate immune cells than adaptive, refers to IgM antibodies made independently of an immune response that demonstrate polyreactivity—i.e. they recognize multiple distinct (unrelated) antigens.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] These can work with the complement system in the earliest phases of an immune response to help facilitate clearance of the offending antigen and delivery of the resulting immune complexes to the lymph nodes or spleen for initiation of an immune response.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Hence in this capacity, the functions of antibodies are more akin to that of innate immunity than adaptive.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies arise from antibody-secreting cells, a term that encompasses plasmablasts and plasma cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In the course of an immune response, B cells can progressively differentiate into antibody-secreting cells or into memory B cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Plasmablasts and plasma cells differ mainly in the degree to which they secrete antibodies, their lifespan, metabolic adaptations, and surface markers.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Plasmablasts are rapidly proliferating, short-lived cells produced in the early phases of the immune response (classically described as arising from extrafollicular reactions rather than from a germinal center) which have the potential to differentiate further into plasma cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Occasionally plasmablasts are mis-described as short-lived plasma cells; formally this is incorrect because plasma cells do not divide (they are terminally differentiated), and rely on survival niches comprising specific cell types and cytokines to persist.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] It is commonly said that plasma cells do not express surface immunoglobulin (whereas plasmablasts do), but this depends on the class of antibody that the plasma cell generates (IgG-secreting plasma cells do not, but IgM, IgA, and IgE plasma cells do).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Plasma cells will secrete huge quantities of antibody regardless of whether or not antigen is present, ensuring that antibody levels to the antigen in question do not fall to zero, provided the plasma cell stays alive.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The rate of antibody secretion, however, can be regulated, for example, by the presence of adjuvant molecules that stimulate the immune response such as toll-like receptor ligands.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Long-lived plasma cells can live for potentially the entire lifetime of the organism.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Classically, the survival niches that house long-lived plasma cells reside in the bone marrow, though it cannot be assumed that any given plasma cell in the bone marrow will be long-lived.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] However, other work indicates that survival niches can readily be established within the mucosal tissues, though the classes of antibodies involved show a different hierarchy from those in the bone marrow.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] B cells can also differentiate into memory B cells which can persist for decades, similarly to long-lived plasma cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] These cells can be rapidly recalled in a secondary immune response, undergoing class switching, affinity maturation, and differentiating into antibody-secreting cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies are heavy (~150 kDa) proteins of about 10 nm in size, arranged in three globular regions that roughly form a Y shape.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In humans and most other mammals, an antibody unit consists of four polypeptide chains; two identical *heavy chains* and two identical *light chains* connected by disulfide bonds.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Each chain is a series of domains: somewhat similar sequences of about 110 amino acids each.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] These domains are usually represented in simplified schematics as rectangles.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Light chains consist of one variable domain VL and one constant domain CL, while heavy chains contain one variable domain VH and three to four constant domains CH1, CH2, ...
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Structurally an antibody is also partitioned into two antigen-binding fragments (Fab), containing one VL, VH, CL, and CH1 domain each, as well as the crystallisable fragment (Fc), forming the trunk of the Y shape.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In between them is a hinge region of the heavy chains, whose flexibility allows antibodies to bind to pairs of epitopes at various distances, to form complexes (dimers, trimers, etc.), and to bind effector molecules more easily.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In an electrophoresis test of blood proteins, antibodies mostly migrate to the last, gamma globulin fraction.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Conversely, most gamma-globulins are antibodies, which is why the two terms were historically used as synonyms, as were the symbols Ig and γ.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This variant terminology fell out of use due to the correspondence being inexact and due to confusion with γ (gamma) heavy chains which characterize the IgG class of antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The variable domains can also be referred to as the FV region.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] It is the subregion of Fab that binds to an antigen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] More specifically, each variable domain contains three *hypervariable regions* – the amino acids seen there vary the most from antibody to antibody.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] When the protein folds, these regions give rise to three loops of β-strands, localized near one another on the surface of the antibody.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] These loops are referred to as the complementarity-determining regions (CDRs), since their shape complements that of an antigen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Three CDRs from each of the heavy and light chains together form an antibody-binding site whose shape can be anything from a pocket to which a smaller antigen binds, to a larger surface, to a protrusion that sticks out into a groove in an antigen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Typically though, only a few residues contribute to most of the binding energy.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The structures of CDRs have been clustered and classified by Chothia et al. and more recently by North et al. and Nikoloudis et al.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] However, describing an antibody's binding site using only one single static structure limits the understanding and characterization of the antibody's function and properties.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] To improve antibody structure prediction and to take the strongly correlated CDR loop and interface movements into account, antibody paratopes should be described as interconverting states in solution with varying probabilities.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In the framework of the immune network theory, CDRs are also called idiotypes.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] According to immune network theory, the adaptive immune system is regulated by interactions between idiotypes.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The Fc region (the trunk of the Y shape) is composed of constant domains from the heavy chains.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Its role is in modulating immune cell activity: it is where effector molecules bind to, triggering various effects after the antibody Fab region binds to an antigen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Effector cells (such as macrophages or natural killer cells) bind via their Fc receptors (FcR) to the Fc region of an antibody, while the complement system is activated by binding the C1q protein complex (also via the Fc region).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] IgG or IgM can bind to C1q, but IgA cannot, therefore IgA does not activate the classical complement pathway.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Another role of the Fc region is to selectively distribute different antibody classes across the body.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In particular, the neonatal Fc receptor (FcRn) binds to the Fc region of IgG antibodies to transport it across the placenta, from the mother to the fetus.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In addition to this, binding to FcRn endows IgG with an exceptionally long half-life relative to other plasma proteins of 3–4 weeks.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] IgG3 in most cases (depending on allotype) has mutations at the FcRn binding site which lower affinity for FcRn, which are thought to have evolved to limit the highly inflammatory effects of this subclass.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies are glycoproteins, that is, they have carbohydrates (glycans) added to conserved amino acid residues.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] These conserved glycosylation sites occur in the Fc region and influence interactions with effector molecules.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The N-terminus of each chain is situated at the tip.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Each immunoglobulin domain has a similar structure, characteristic of all the members of the immunoglobulin superfamily: it is composed of between 7 (for constant domains) and 9 (for variable domains) β-strands, forming two beta sheets in a Greek key motif.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The sheets create a "sandwich" shape, the immunoglobulin fold, held together by a disulfide bond.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Secreted antibodies can occur as a single Y-shaped unit, a monomer.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] However, some antibody classes also form dimers with two Ig units (as with IgA), tetramers with four Ig units (like teleost fish IgM), or pentamers with five Ig units (like shark IgW or mammalian IgM, which occasionally forms hexamers as well, with six units).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] IgG can also form hexamers, though no J chain is required.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] IgA tetramers and pentamers have also been reported.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies also form complexes by binding to antigen: this is called an antigen-antibody complex or *immune complex*.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Small antigens can cross-link two antibodies, also leading to the formation of antibody dimers, trimers, tetramers, etc.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Multivalent antigens (e.g., cells with multiple epitopes) can form larger complexes with antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] An extreme example is the clumping, or agglutination, of red blood cells with antibodies in blood typing to determine blood groups: the large clumps become insoluble, leading to visually apparent precipitation.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The membrane-bound form of an antibody may be called a *surface immunoglobulin* (sIg) or a *membrane immunoglobulin* (mIg).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] It is part of the *B cell receptor* (BCR), which allows a B cell to detect when a specific antigen is present in the body and triggers B cell activation.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The BCR is composed of surface-bound IgD or IgM antibodies and associated Ig-α and Ig-β heterodimers, which are capable of signal transduction.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] A typical human B cell will have 50,000 to 100,000 antibodies bound to its surface.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Upon antigen binding, they cluster in large patches, which can exceed 1 micrometer in diameter, on lipid rafts that isolate the BCRs from most other cell signaling receptors.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] These patches may improve the efficiency of the cellular immune response.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In humans, the cell surface is bare around the B cell receptors for several hundred nanometers, which further isolates the BCRs from competing influences.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies can come in different varieties known as *isotypes* or *classes*.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In humans there are five antibody classes known as IgA, IgD, IgE, IgG, and IgM, which are further subdivided into subclasses such as IgA1, IgA2.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The prefix "Ig" stands for *immunoglobulin*, while the suffix denotes the type of heavy chain the antibody contains: the heavy chain types α (alpha), γ (gamma), δ (delta), ε (epsilon), μ (mu) give rise to IgA, IgG, IgD, IgE, IgM, respectively.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The distinctive features of each class are determined by the part of the heavy chain within the hinge and Fc region.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The classes differ in their biological properties, functional locations and ability to deal with different antigens, as depicted in the table.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] For example, IgE antibodies are responsible for an allergic response consisting of histamine release from mast cells, often a sole contributor to asthma (though other pathways exist as do symptoms very similar to yet not technically asthma).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The variable region of these antibodies bind to allergic antigen, for example house dust mite particles, while its Fc region (in the ε heavy chains) binds to Fc receptor ε on a mast cell, triggering its degranulation: the release of molecules stored in its granules.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The antibody isotype of a B cell changes during cell development and activation.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Immature B cells, which have never been exposed to an antigen, express only the IgM isotype in a cell surface bound form.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The B lymphocyte, in this ready-to-respond form, is known as a "naive B lymphocyte." The naive B lymphocyte expresses both surface IgM and IgD.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The co-expression of both of these immunoglobulin isotypes renders the B cell ready to respond to antigen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] B cell activation follows engagement of the cell-bound antibody molecule with an antigen, causing the cell to divide and differentiate into an antibody-producing cell called a plasma cell.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This requires cytokines from T helper cells, unless antigen cross-links B cell receptors.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In this activated form, the B cell starts to produce antibody in a secreted form rather than a membrane-bound form.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Activated B cells that encounter certain signaling molecules undergo immunoglobulin class switching, also known as isotype switching, which causes the production of antibodies to change from IgM or IgD to the other antibody isotypes, IgE, IgA, or IgG.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In mammals there are two types of immunoglobulin light chain, which are called lambda (λ) and kappa (κ).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] However, there is no known functional difference between them, and both can occur with any of the five major types of heavy chains.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Each antibody contains two identical light chains: both κ or both λ.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Proportions of κ and λ types vary by species and can be used to detect abnormal proliferation of B cell clones.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Other types of light chains, such as the iota (ι) chain, are found in other vertebrates like sharks (Chondrichthyes) and bony fishes (Teleostei).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Though there is no known functional significance to the different choice of light chain class, the ratio of light chains can be diagnostically useful.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] For example, humans normally have a ratio of 2:1 of κ:λ light chains, and significant deviation from this ratio can indicate the presence of a monoclonal gammopathy (in which there is a proliferation of a plasma cell which may or may not be pre-malignant or malignant).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In most placental mammals, the structure of antibodies is generally similar.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Jawed fish appear to be the most primitive animals that are able to make antibodies similar to those of mammals, although many features of their adaptive immunity appeared somewhat earlier.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Cartilaginous fish (such as sharks) produce heavy-chain-only antibodies (i.e., lacking light chains) which moreover feature longer chain pentamers (with five constant units per molecule).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Camelids (such as camels, llamas, alpacas) are also notable for producing heavy-chain-only antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The antibody's paratope interacts with the antigen's epitope.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] An antigen usually contains different epitopes along its surface arranged discontinuously, and dominant epitopes on a given antigen are called determinants.Antibody and antigen interact by spatial complementarity (lock and key).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The molecular forces involved in the Fab-epitope interaction are weak and non-specific – for example electrostatic forces, hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions, and van der Waals forces.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This means binding between antibody and antigen is reversible, and the antibody's affinity towards an antigen is relative rather than absolute.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Relatively weak binding also means it is possible for an antibody to cross-react with different antigens of different relative affinities.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] More indirectly, an antibody can signal immune cells to present antibody fragments to T cells, or downregulate other immune cells to avoid autoimmunity.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] At the prenatal and neonatal stages of life, the presence of antibodies is provided by passive immunity from the mother through transplacental transfer of IgG antibodies and breastmilk antibodies (predominantly secretory IgA in humans).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] There are also important species-specific differences in the structure of the placenta, which complicates interpretations of how placental transfer of antibody works in humans.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Early endogenous antibody production varies for different kinds of antibodies, and usually appear within the first years of life.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Since antibodies exist freely in the bloodstream, they are said to be part of the humoral immune system.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Circulating antibodies (other than natural IgM) are produced by clonal B cells that specifically respond to only one antigen (unless the antibodies recognize an epitope with structural similarity across many different antigens).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies will also trigger vasoactive amine degranulation to contribute to immunity against certain types of antigens (helminths, allergens).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies that bind to surface antigens (for example, on bacteria) will attract the first component of the complement cascade with their Fc region and initiate activation of the "classical" complement system.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This results in the killing of bacteria in two ways.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] First, the binding of the antibody and complement molecules marks the microbe for ingestion by phagocytes in a process called opsonization; these phagocytes are attracted by certain complement molecules generated in the complement cascade.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Second, some complement system components form a membrane attack complex to assist antibodies to kill the bacterium directly (bacteriolysis).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] To combat pathogens that replicate outside cells, antibodies bind to pathogens to link them together, causing them to agglutinate.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Since an antibody has at least two paratopes, it can bind more than one antigen by binding identical epitopes carried on the surfaces of these antigens.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] By coating the pathogen, antibodies stimulate effector functions against the pathogen in cells that recognize their Fc region.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Those cells that recognize coated pathogens have Fc receptors, which, as the name suggests, interact with the Fc region of IgA, IgG, and IgE antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The activation of natural killer cells by antibodies initiates a cytotoxic mechanism known as antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity (ADCC) – this process may explain the efficacy of monoclonal antibodies used in biological therapies against cancer.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The Fc receptors are isotype-specific, which gives greater flexibility to the immune system, invoking only the appropriate immune mechanisms for distinct pathogens.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Humans and higher primates also produce "natural antibodies" that are present in serum before viral infection.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Natural antibodies have been defined as antibodies that are produced without any previous infection, vaccination, other foreign antigen exposure or passive immunization.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] These antibodies can activate the classical complement pathway leading to lysis of enveloped virus particles long before the adaptive immune response is activated.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies are produced exclusively by B cells in response to antigens where initially, antibodies are formed as membrane-bound receptors, but upon activation by antigens and helper T cells, B cells differentiate to produce soluble antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Many natural antibodies are directed against the disaccharide galactose α(1,3)-galactose (α-Gal), which is found as a terminal sugar on glycosylated cell surface proteins, and generated in response to production of this sugar by bacteria contained in the human gut.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] These antibodies undergo quality checks in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER), which contains proteins that assist in proper folding and assembly.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Rejection of xenotransplantated organs is thought to be, in part, the result of natural antibodies circulating in the serum of the recipient binding to α-Gal antigens expressed on the donor tissue.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibodies are central to the immune protection elicited by most vaccines (although other components of the immune system certainly participate and for some diseases are considerably more important than antibodies in generating an immune response, such as in the case of shingles).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] At the same time, many microbes of medical importance have the ability to mutate to escape antibodies elicited by prior infections, and long-lived plasma cells cannot undergo affinity maturation or class switching.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This is compensated for through memory B cells: novel variants of a microbe that still retain structural features of previously encountered antigens can elicit memory B cell responses that adapt to those changes.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] It has been suggested that long-lived plasma cells secrete B cell receptors with higher affinity than those on the surfaces of memory B cells, but findings are not entirely consistent on this point.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Virtually all microbes can trigger an antibody response.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Successful recognition and eradication of many different types of microbes requires diversity among antibodies; their amino acid composition varies allowing them to interact with many different antigens.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] It has been estimated that humans generate about 10 billion different antibodies, each capable of binding a distinct epitope of an antigen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Although a huge repertoire of different antibodies is generated in a single individual, the number of genes available to make these proteins is limited by the size of the human genome.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Several complex genetic mechanisms have evolved that allow vertebrate B cells to generate a diverse pool of antibodies from a relatively small number of antibody genes.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] One of these domains is called the variable domain, which is present in each heavy and light chain of every antibody, but can differ in different antibodies generated from distinct B cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Differences between the variable domains are located on three loops known as hypervariable regions (HV-1, HV-2 and HV-3) or complementarity-determining regions (CDR1, CDR2 and CDR3).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] CDRs are supported within the variable domains by conserved framework regions.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The heavy chain locus contains about 65 different variable domain genes that all differ in their CDRs.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Combining these genes with an array of genes for other domains of the antibody generates a large cavalry of antibodies with a high degree of variability.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This combination is called V(D)J recombination and discussed below.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Somatic recombination of immunoglobulins, also known as *V(D)J recombination*, involves the generation of a unique immunoglobulin variable region.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The variable region of each immunoglobulin heavy or light chain is encoded in several pieces—known as gene segments (subgenes).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] These segments are called variable (V), diversity (D) and joining (J) segments.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] V, D and J segments are found in Ig heavy chains, but only V and J segments are found in Ig light chains.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Multiple copies of the V, D and J gene segments exist, and are tandemly arranged in the genomes of mammals.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In the bone marrow, each developing B cell will assemble an immunoglobulin variable region by randomly selecting and combining one V, one D and one J gene segment (or one V and one J segment in the light chain).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] As there are multiple copies of each type of gene segment, and different combinations of gene segments can be used to generate each immunoglobulin variable region, this process generates a huge number of antibodies, each with different paratopes, and thus different antigen specificities.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The rearrangement of several subgenes (i.e.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] V2 family) for lambda light chain immunoglobulin is coupled with the activation of microRNA miR-650, which further influences biology of B-cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] RAG proteins play an important role with V(D)J recombination in cutting DNA at a particular region.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Without the presence of these proteins, V(D)J recombination would not occur.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] After a B cell produces a functional immunoglobulin gene during V(D)J recombination, it cannot express any other variable region (a process known as allelic exclusion) thus each B cell can produce antibodies containing only one kind of variable chain.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Following activation with antigen, B cells begin to proliferate rapidly.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In these rapidly dividing cells, the genes encoding the variable domains of the heavy and light chains undergo a high rate of point mutation, by a process called *somatic hypermutation* (SHM).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] SHM results in approximately one nucleotide change per variable gene, per cell division.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] As a consequence, any daughter B cells will acquire slight amino acid differences in the variable domains of their antibody chains.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This serves to increase the diversity of the antibody pool and impacts the antibody's antigen-binding affinity.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Some point mutations will result in the production of antibodies that have a weaker interaction (low affinity) with their antigen than the original antibody, and some mutations will generate antibodies with a stronger interaction (high affinity).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] B cells that express high affinity antibodies on their surface will receive a strong survival signal during interactions with other cells, whereas those with low affinity antibodies will not, and will die by apoptosis.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Thus, B cells expressing antibodies with a higher affinity for the antigen will outcompete those with weaker affinities for function and survival allowing the average affinity of antibodies to increase over time.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The process of generating antibodies with increased binding affinities is called *affinity maturation*.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Affinity maturation occurs in mature B cells after V(D)J recombination, and is dependent on help from helper T cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Isotype or class switching is a biological process occurring after activation of the B cell, which allows the cell to produce different classes of antibody (IgA, IgE, or IgG).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The different classes of antibody, and thus effector functions, are defined by the constant (C) regions of the immunoglobulin heavy chain.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Initially, naive B cells express only cell-surface IgM and IgD with identical antigen binding regions.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Each isotype is adapted for a distinct function; therefore, after activation, an antibody with an IgG, IgA, or IgE effector function might be required to effectively eliminate an antigen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Class switching allows different daughter cells from the same activated B cell to produce antibodies of different isotypes.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Only the constant region of the antibody heavy chain changes during class switching; the variable regions, and therefore antigen specificity, remain unchanged.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Thus the progeny of a single B cell can produce antibodies, all specific for the same antigen, but with the ability to produce the effector function appropriate for each antigenic challenge.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Class switching is triggered by cytokines; the isotype generated depends on which cytokines are present in the B cell environment.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Class switching occurs in the heavy chain gene locus by a mechanism called class switch recombination (CSR).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This mechanism relies on conserved nucleotide motifs, called *switch (S) regions*, found in DNA upstream of each constant region gene (except in the δ-chain).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The DNA strand is broken by the activity of a series of enzymes at two selected S-regions.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The variable domain exon is rejoined through a process called non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) to the desired constant region (γ, α or ε).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This process results in an immunoglobulin gene that encodes an antibody of a different isotype.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] An antibody can be called *monospecific* if it has specificity for a single antigen or epitope, or bispecific if it has affinity for two different antigens or two different epitopes on the same antigen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] A group of antibodies can be called *polyvalent* (or *unspecific*) if they have affinity for various antigens or microorganisms.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Intravenous immunoglobulin, if not otherwise noted, consists of a variety of different IgG (polyclonal IgG).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In contrast, monoclonal antibodies are identical antibodies produced by a single B cell.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Heterodimeric antibodies, which are also asymmetrical antibodies, allow for greater flexibility and new formats for attaching a variety of drugs to the antibody arms.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] One of the general formats for a heterodimeric antibody is the "knobs-into-holes" format.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This format is specific to the heavy chain part of the constant region in antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The "knobs" part is engineered by replacing a small amino acid with a larger one.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] It fits into the "hole", which is engineered by replacing a large amino acid with a smaller one.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] What connects the "knobs" to the "holes" are the disulfide bonds between each chain.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The "knobs-into-holes" shape facilitates antibody dependent cell mediated cytotoxicity.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Single-chain variable fragments (scFv) are connected to the variable domain of the heavy and light chain via a short linker peptide.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The linker is rich in glycine, which gives it more flexibility, and serine/threonine, which gives it specificity.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Two different scFv fragments can be connected together, via a hinge region, to the constant domain of the heavy chain or the constant domain of the light chain.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This gives the antibody bispecificity, allowing for the binding specificities of two different antigens.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The "knobs-into-holes" format enhances heterodimer formation but does not suppress homodimer formation.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] To further improve the function of heterodimeric antibodies, many scientists are looking towards artificial constructs.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Artificial antibodies are largely diverse protein motifs that use the functional strategy of the antibody molecule, but are not limited by the loop and framework structural constraints of the natural antibody.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Controlling the combinational design of the sequence and the resulting three-dimensional space could enhance the natural design and allow for the attachment of different combinations of drugs to the arms.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Heterodimeric antibodies have a greater range in shapes they can take and the drugs that are attached to the arms do not have to be the same on each arm, allowing for different combinations of drugs to be used in cancer treatment.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Pharmaceuticals are able to produce highly functional bispecific, and even multispecific, antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The degree to which they can function is impressive given that such a change of shape from the natural form should lead to decreased functionality.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Antibody diversification typically occurs through somatic hypermutation, class switching, and affinity maturation targeting the BCR gene loci, but on occasion more unconventional forms of diversification have been documented.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] For example, in the case of malaria caused by *Plasmodium falciparum,* some antibodies from those who had been infected demonstrated an insertion from chromosome 19 containing a 98-amino acid stretch from leukocyte-associated immunoglobulin-like receptor 1, LAIR1, in the elbow joint.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This represents a form of interchromosomal transposition.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] LAIR1 normally binds collagen, but can recognize repetitive interspersed families of polypeptides (RIFIN) family members that are highly expressed on the surface of *P. falciparum*-infected red blood cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In fact, these antibodies underwent affinity maturation that enhanced affinity for RIFIN but abolished affinity for collagen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] These "LAIR1-containing" antibodies have been found in 5-10% of donors from Tanzania and Mali, though not in European donors.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] European donors did show 100-1000 nucleotide stretches inside the elbow joints as well, however.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] This particular phenomenon may be specific to malaria, as infection is known to induce genomic instability.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The first use of the term "antibody" occurred in a text by Paul Ehrlich.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The term *Antikörper* (the German word for *antibody*) appears in the conclusion of his article "Experimental Studies on Immunity", published in October 1891, which states that, "if two substances give rise to two different *Antikörper*, then they themselves must be different".
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] However, the term was not accepted immediately and several other terms for antibody were proposed; these included *Immunkörper*, *Amboceptor*, *Zwischenkörper*, *substance sensibilisatrice*, *copula*, *Desmon*, *philocytase*, *fixateur*, and *Immunisin*.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The word *antibody* has formal analogy to the word *antitoxin* and a similar concept to *Immunkörper* (*immune body* in English).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] As such, the original construction of the word contains a logical flaw; the antitoxin is something directed against a toxin, while the antibody is a body directed against something.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The study of antibodies began in 1890 when Emil von Behring and Kitasato Shibasaburō described antibody activity against diphtheria and tetanus toxins.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Von Behring and Kitasato put forward the theory of humoral immunity, proposing that a mediator in serum could react with a foreign antigen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Other researchers believed that antibodies existed freely in the blood and, in 1904, Almroth Wright suggested that soluble antibodies coated bacteria to label them for phagocytosis and killing; a process that he named opsoninization.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In the 1920s, Michael Heidelberger and Oswald Avery observed that antigens could be precipitated by antibodies and went on to show that antibodies are made of protein.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The biochemical properties of antigen-antibody-binding interactions were examined in more detail in the late 1930s by John Marrack.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The next major advance was in the 1940s, when Linus Pauling confirmed the lock-and-key theory proposed by Ehrlich by showing that the interactions between antibodies and antigens depend more on their shape than their chemical composition.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In 1948, Astrid Fagraeus discovered that B cells, in the form of plasma cells, were responsible for generating antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Further work concentrated on characterizing the structures of the antibody proteins.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] A major advance in these structural studies was the discovery in the early 1960s by Gerald Edelman and Joseph Gally of the antibody light chain, and their realization that this protein is the same as the Bence-Jones protein described in 1845 by Henry Bence Jones.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Edelman went on to discover that antibodies are composed of disulfide bond-linked heavy and light chains.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Around the same time, antibody-binding (Fab) and antibody tail (Fc) regions of IgG were characterized by Rodney Porter.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Together, these scientists deduced the structure and complete amino acid sequence of IgG, a feat for which they were jointly awarded the 1972 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] The Fv fragment was prepared and characterized by David Givol.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] While most of these early studies focused on IgM and IgG, other immunoglobulin isotypes were identified in the 1960s: Thomas Tomasi discovered secretory antibody (IgA); David S.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] Fahey discovered IgD; and Kimishige Ishizaka and Teruko Ishizaka discovered IgE and showed it was a class of antibodies involved in allergic reactions.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p01] In a landmark series of experiments beginning in 1976, Susumu Tonegawa showed that genetic material can rearrange itself to form the vast array of available antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Detection of particular antibodies is a very common form of medical diagnostics, and applications such as serology depend on these methods.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] For example, in biochemical assays for disease diagnosis, a titer of antibodies directed against Epstein–Barr virus or Lyme disease is estimated from the blood.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] If those antibodies are not present, either the person is not infected or the infection occurred a *very* long time ago, and the B cells generating these specific antibodies have naturally decayed.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] In clinical immunology, levels of individual classes of immunoglobulins are measured by nephelometry (or turbidimetry) to characterize the antibody profile of patient.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Elevations in different classes of immunoglobulins are sometimes useful in determining the cause of liver damage in patients for whom the diagnosis is unclear.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] For example, IgM levels are often elevated in patients with primary biliary cirrhosis, whereas IgA deposition along hepatic sinusoids can suggest alcoholic liver disease.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Autoimmune disorders can often be traced to antibodies that bind the body's own epitopes; many can be detected through blood tests.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Antibodies directed against red blood cell surface antigens in immune mediated hemolytic anemia are detected with the Coombs test.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] The Coombs test is also used for antibody screening in blood transfusion preparation and also for antibody screening in antenatal women.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] New dioxaborolane chemistry enables radioactive fluoride (18F) labeling of antibodies, which allows for positron emission tomography (PET) imaging of cancer.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Targeted monoclonal antibody therapy is employed to treat diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis, multiple sclerosis, psoriasis, and many forms of cancer including non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, colorectal cancer, head and neck cancer and breast cancer.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Some immune deficiencies, such as X-linked agammaglobulinemia and hypogammaglobulinemia, result in partial or complete lack of antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] These diseases are often treated by inducing a short-term form of immunity called passive immunity.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Passive immunity is achieved through the transfer of ready-made antibodies in the form of human or animal serum, pooled immunoglobulin or monoclonal antibodies, into the affected individual.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Rh factor, also known as Rh D antigen, is an antigen found on red blood cells; individuals that are Rh-positive (Rh+) have this antigen on their red blood cells and individuals that are Rh-negative (Rh–) do not.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] During normal childbirth, delivery trauma or complications during pregnancy, blood from a fetus can enter the mother's system.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] In the case of an Rh-incompatible mother and child, consequential blood mixing may sensitize an Rh- mother to the Rh antigen on the blood cells of the Rh+ child, putting the remainder of the pregnancy, and any subsequent pregnancies, at risk for hemolytic disease of the newborn.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Rho(D) immune globulin antibodies are specific for human RhD antigen.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Anti-RhD antibodies are administered as part of a prenatal treatment regimen to prevent sensitization that may occur when a Rh-negative mother has a Rh-positive fetus.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Treatment of a mother with Anti-RhD antibodies prior to and immediately after trauma and delivery destroys Rh antigen in the mother's system from the fetus.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] This occurs before the antigen can stimulate maternal B cells to "remember" Rh antigen by generating memory B cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Therefore, her humoral immune system will not make anti-Rh antibodies, and will not attack the Rh antigens of the current or subsequent babies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Rho(D) Immune Globulin treatment prevents sensitization that can lead to Rh disease, but does not prevent or treat the underlying disease itself.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Specific antibodies are produced by injecting an antigen into a mammal, such as a mouse, rat, rabbit, goat, sheep, horse, or human for large quantities of antibody.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Blood isolated from these animals contains *polyclonal antibodies*—multiple antibodies that bind to the same antigen—in the serum, which can now be called antiserum.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] (For medical products, the horse and the human are most commonly used: the former for its large blood volume and high antibody titers, the latter for a higher compatibility with other humans.) Antigens are also injected into chickens for generation of polyclonal antibodies in egg yolk.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] To obtain antibody that is specific for a single epitope of an antigen, antibody-secreting lymphocytes are isolated from the animal and immortalized by fusing them with a cancer cell line.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] The fused cells are called hybridomas, and will continually grow and secrete antibody in culture.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Single hybridoma cells are isolated by dilution cloning to generate cell clones that all produce the same antibody; these antibodies are called *monoclonal antibodies*.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Polyclonal and monoclonal antibodies are often purified using Protein A/G or antigen-affinity chromatography.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] In research, purified antibodies are used in many applications.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Antibodies for research applications can be found directly from antibody suppliers, or through use of a specialist search engine.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Research antibodies are most commonly used to identify and locate intracellular and extracellular proteins.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Antibodies are used in flow cytometry to differentiate cell types by the proteins they express; different types of cells express different combinations of cluster of differentiation molecules on their surface, and produce different intracellular and secretable proteins.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Proteins can also be detected and quantified with antibodies, using ELISA and ELISpot techniques.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Multiple attempts have been made to improve both the way that researchers validate antibodies and ways in which they report on antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Researchers using antibodies in their work need to record them correctly in order to allow their research to be reproducible (and therefore tested, and qualified by other researchers).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Less than half of research antibodies referenced in academic papers can be easily identified.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Papers published in F1000 in 2014 and 2015 provide researchers with a guide for reporting research antibody use.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] The RRID paper, is co-published in 4 journals that implemented the RRIDs Standard for research resource citation, which draws data from the antibodyregistry.org as the source of antibody identifiers (see also group at Force11).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Antibody regions can be used to further biomedical research by acting as a guide for drugs to reach their target.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Antibodies and Fc‑based constructs provide highly specific binding to cell-surface receptors and are used as targeting moieties in antibody–drug conjugates (ADCs), bispecifics, and Fc‑fusion drugs for cancer and other diseases.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] There are several ways to obtain antibodies, including *in vivo* techniques like animal immunization and various *in vitro* approaches, such as the phage display method.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Traditionally, most antibodies are produced by hybridoma cell lines through immortalization of antibody-producing cells by chemically induced fusion with myeloma cells.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] In some cases, additional fusions with other lines have created "triomas" and "quadromas".
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] The manufacturing process should be appropriately described and validated.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] The importance of antibodies in health care and the biotechnology industry demands knowledge of their structures at high resolution.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] This information is used for protein engineering, modifying the antigen binding affinity, and identifying an epitope, of a given antibody.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] X-ray crystallography is one commonly used method for determining antibody structures.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] However, crystallizing an antibody is often laborious and time-consuming.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Computational approaches provide a cheaper and faster alternative to crystallography, but their results are more equivocal, since they do not produce empirical structures.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Online web servers such as *Web Antibody Modeling* (WAM) and *Prediction of Immunoglobulin Structure* (PIGS) enable computational modeling of antibody variable regions.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] The ability to describe the antibody through binding affinity to the antigen is supplemented by information on antibody structure and amino acid sequences for the purpose of patent claims.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Several methods have been presented for computational design of antibodies based on the structural bioinformatics studies of antibody CDRs.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] There are a variety of methods used to sequence an antibody including Edman degradation, cDNA, etc.; albeit one of the most common modern uses for peptide/protein identification is liquid chromatography coupled with tandem mass spectrometry (LC-MS/MS).
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] High volume antibody sequencing methods require computational approaches for the data analysis, including de novo sequencing directly from tandem mass spectra and database search methods that use existing protein sequence databases.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Many versions of shotgun protein sequencing are able to increase the coverage by utilizing CID/HCD/ETD fragmentation methods and other techniques, and they have achieved substantial progress in attempt to fully sequence proteins, especially antibodies.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Other methods have assumed the existence of similar proteins, a known genome sequence, or combined top-down and bottom up approaches.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Current technologies have the ability to assemble protein sequences with high accuracy by integrating de novo sequencing peptides, intensity, and positional confidence scores from database and homology searches.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Antibody mimetics are organic compounds, like antibodies, that can specifically bind antigens.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] They consist of artificial peptides or proteins, or aptamer-based nucleic acid molecules with a molar mass of about 3 to 20 kDa.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Antibody fragments, such as Fab and nanobodies are not considered as antibody mimetics.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Common advantages over antibodies are better solubility, tissue penetration, stability towards heat and enzymes, and comparatively low production costs.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] Antibody mimetics have been developed and commercialized as research, diagnostic and therapeutic agents.
[src:immune-response/antibody-p02] BAU (binding antibody unit, often as BAU/mL) is a measurement unit defined by the WHO for the comparison of assays detecting the same class of immunoglobulins with the same specificity.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] An **antigen-presenting cell** (**APC**) or **accessory cell** is a cell that displays an antigen bound by major histocompatibility complex (MHC) proteins on its surface; this process is known as antigen presentation.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] T cells may recognize these complexes using their T cell receptors (TCRs).
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] APCs process antigens and present them to T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Almost all cell types can present antigens in some way.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] They are found in a variety of tissue types.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Dedicated antigen-presenting cells, including macrophages, B cells and dendritic cells, present foreign antigens to helper T cells, while virus-infected cells (or cancer cells) can present antigens originating inside the cell to cytotoxic T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] In addition to the MHC family of proteins, antigen presentation relies on other specialized signaling molecules on the surfaces of both APCs and T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Antigen-presenting cells are vital for effective adaptive immune response, as the functioning of both cytotoxic and helper T cells is dependent on APCs.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Antigen presentation allows for specificity of adaptive immunity and can contribute to immune responses against both intracellular and extracellular pathogens.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] It is also involved in defense against tumors.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Some cancer therapies involve the creation of artificial APCs to prime the adaptive immune system to target malignant cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Antigen-presenting cells fall into two categories: professional and non-professional.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Those that express MHC class II molecules along with co-stimulatory molecules and pattern recognition receptors are often called **professional antigen-presenting cells**.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] The non-professional APCs express MHC class I molecules.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] T cells must be activated before they can divide and perform their function.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] This is achieved by interacting with a professional APC which presents an antigen recognized by their T cell receptor.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] The APC involved in activating T cells is usually a dendritic cell.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] T cells cannot recognize (and therefore cannot respond to) "free" or soluble antigens.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] They can only recognize and respond to antigen that has been processed and presented by cells via carrier molecules like MHC molecules.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Helper T cells can recognize exogenous antigen presented on MHC class II; cytotoxic T cells can recognize endogenous antigen presented on MHC class I.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Most cells in the body can present antigen to CD8+ cytotoxic T cells via MHC class I; however, the term "antigen-presenting cell" is often used specifically to describe professional APCs.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Such cells express MHC class I and MHC class II molecules and can stimulate CD4+ helper T cells as well as cytotoxic T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] APCs can also present foreign and self lipids to T cells and natural killer cells by using the CD1 family of proteins, which are structurally similar to the MHC class I family.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Professional APCs describe those APCs which are capable of delivering all 3 signals needed to activate a naive T cell (signal 1- the antigen itself, the peptide-MHC complex; signal 2 - costimulatory ligand; signal 3- cytokines to guide polarization of the T cell).
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Canonically, the 3 pAPC types are dendritic cells, macrophages, and B cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] They are very efficient at internalizing antigens, either by phagocytosis (e.g. macrophages), or by receptor-mediated endocytosis (B cells), processing the antigen into peptide fragments and then displaying those peptides (bound to a class II MHC molecule) on their membrane.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] The T cell recognizes and interacts with the antigen-class II MHC molecule complex on the membrane of the antigen-presenting cell.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] An additional co-stimulatory signal is then produced by the antigen-presenting cell, leading to activation of the T cell.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] The expression of co-stimulatory molecules and MHC class II are defining features of professional APCs.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] All professional APCs also express MHC class I molecules as well.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] The main types of professional antigen-presenting cells are dendritic cells, macrophages and B cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Dendritic cells have the broadest range of antigen presentation and are necessary for activation of naive T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] DCs present antigen to both helper and cytotoxic T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] They can also perform cross-presentation, a process by which they present exogenous antigen on MHC class I molecules to cytotoxic T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Cross-presentation allows for the activation of these T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Dendritic cells also play a role in peripheral tolerance, which contributes to prevention of auto-immune disease.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Prior to encountering foreign antigen, dendritic cells express very low levels of MHC class II and co-stimulatory molecules on their cell surface.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] These immature dendritic cells are ineffective at presenting antigen to T helper cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Once a dendritic cell's pattern-recognition receptors recognize a pathogen-associated molecular pattern, antigen is phagocytosed and the dendritic cell becomes activated, upregulating the expression of MHC class II molecules.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] It also upregulates several co-stimulatory molecules required for T cell activation, including CD40 and B7.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] The latter can interact with CD28 on the surface of a CD4+ T cell.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] The dendritic cell is then a fully mature professional APC.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] It moves from the tissue to lymph nodes, where it encounters and activates T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Macrophages can be stimulated by T cell secretion of interferon.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] After this activation, macrophages are able to express MHC class II and co-stimulatory molecules, including the B7 complex and can present phagocytosed peptide fragments to helper T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Activation can assist pathogen-infected macrophages in clearing the infection.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Deriving from monocytes, a type of white blood cell, they will circulate in the blood and enter affected sites and differentiate from monocytes to macrophages.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] At the affected site, the macrophage surrounds the site of infection or tissue damage with its membrane in a mechanism called phagocytosis.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] B cells can internalize antigen that binds to their B cell receptor and present it to helper T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Unlike T cells, B cells can recognize soluble antigen for which their B cell receptor is specific.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] They can then process the antigen and present peptides using MHC class II molecules.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] When a T helper cell with a TCR specific for that peptide binds, the B cell marker CD40 binds to CD40L on the T cell surface.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] When activated by a T cell, a B cell can undergo antibody isotype switching, affinity maturation, as well as formation of memory cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Non-professional antigen presenting cells include all nucleated cell types in the body.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] They use an MHC class I molecule coupled to beta-2 microglobulin to display endogenous peptides on the cell membrane.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] These peptides originate within the cell itself, in contrast to the exogenous antigen displayed by professional APCs using MHC class II molecules.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Cytotoxic T cells are able to interact with endogenous antigen presented using an MHC class I molecule.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Non-professional APCs do not typically express MHC class II molecules.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] However, it has been observed that antigen presentation to CD4+ cells via MHC class II is not restricted to the classically professional APCs.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Other leukocytes, including granulocytes such as mast cells and neutrophils, can be induced to do so, as can endothelial and epithelial cells under certain circumstances.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Even so, there is little evidence that these atypical APCs are able to activate naive CD4+ T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] After dendritic cells have phagocytosed pathogens, they usually migrate to the vast network of lymph vessels and are carried by lymph flow to the draining lymph nodes.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Each lymph node is a collection point where APCs can interact with T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] During the migration, DCs undergo a process of maturation: they lose most of their ability to further engulf pathogens and they mature by changing surface expression of MHC and co-stimulatory molecules, as well as increased production of cytokines.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] The internalized antigen is digested into smaller peptides containing epitopes, which are then presented to T cells by the MHC.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Once their B cell receptor binds to an antigen, they can interact with activated helper T cells, as described above.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] A dendritic cell that interacts with an already-activated helper T cell can become licensed.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] This occurs through the interaction of co-stimulatory molecules including B7 and CD40 on the dendritic cell, with CD28 and CD40 ligand on the T cell.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Only licensed dendritic cells are able to activate cytotoxic T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] T cell licensing of dendritic cells is key for activation of cytotoxic T cells for many pathogens, although the extent to which T cell help is needed may vary.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] In MHC class I and class II molecules, only certain epitopes of an internalized peptide can be presented.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] These epitopes are termed immunodominant.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] APCs naturally have a role in fighting tumors, via stimulation of B and cytotoxic T cells to respectively produce antibodies against tumor-related antigen and kill malignant cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Dendritic cells, presenting tumor-specific antigen to T cells, are key to this process.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Cancer therapies have included treating the patient with increased numbers of dendritic cells or cancer-specific T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] However, newer therapies have turned to genetically engineered artificial antigen-presenting cells designed to prime the immune system to attack malignant cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] Some artificial APCs are derived from human cells; others are acellular, containing MHC proteins, co-stimulatory molecules and the necessary peptides.
[src:immune-response/antigen-presenting-cell] The APC activator IMP321 is being tested in clinical trials to accelerate the immune reaction to eliminate metastatic breast cancer or melanoma.
[src:immune-response/antigen] In immunology, an **antigen** (**Ag**) is a molecule, or portion thereof, that can bind to a specific antibody or T-cell receptor.
[src:immune-response/antigen] The presence of antigens in the body may trigger an immune response.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Antigens can be proteins, peptides (amino acid chains), polysaccharides (chains of simple sugars), lipids, or nucleic acids.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Antigens exist on normal cells, cancer cells, parasites, viruses, fungi, and bacteria.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Antigens are recognized by antigen receptors, including antibodies and T-cell receptors.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Diverse antigen receptors are made by cells of the immune system so that each cell has a specificity for a single antigen.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Upon exposure to an antigen, only the lymphocytes that recognize that antigen are activated and expanded, a process known as clonal selection.
[src:immune-response/antigen] In most cases, antibodies are *antigen-specific*, meaning that an antibody can only react to and bind one specific antigen; in some instances, however, antibodies may cross-react to bind more than one antigen.
[src:immune-response/antigen] The reaction between an antigen and an antibody is called the antigen-antibody reaction.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Antigen can originate either from within the body ("self-protein" or "self antigens") or from the external environment ("non-self").
[src:immune-response/antigen] The immune system identifies and attacks "non-self" external antigens.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Antibodies usually do not react with self-antigens due to negative selection of T cells in the thymus and B cells in the bone marrow.
[src:immune-response/antigen] The diseases in which antibodies react with self antigens and damage the body's own cells are called autoimmune diseases.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Vaccines are examples of antigens in an immunogenic form, which are intentionally administered to a recipient to induce the memory function of the adaptive immune system towards antigens of the pathogen invading that recipient.
[src:immune-response/antigen] The vaccine for seasonal influenza is a common example.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Paul Ehrlich coined the term *antibody* (German: *Antikörper*) in his side-chain theory at the end of the 19th century.
[src:immune-response/antigen] In 1899, Ladislas Deutsch (László Detre) named the hypothetical substances halfway between bacterial constituents and antibodies "antigenic or immunogenic substances" (French: *substances immunogènes ou antigènes*).
[src:immune-response/antigen] He originally believed those substances to be precursors of antibodies, just as a zymogen is a precursor of an enzyme.
[src:immune-response/antigen] But, by 1903, he understood that an antigen induces the production of immune bodies (antibodies) and wrote that the word *antigen* is a contraction of antisomatogen (*Immunkörperbildner*).
[src:immune-response/antigen] The *Oxford English Dictionary* indicates that the logical construction should be "anti(body)-gen".
[src:immune-response/antigen] The term originally referred to a substance that acts as an antibody generator.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Antigens can be proteins, polysaccharides, lipids, nucleic acids or other biomolecules.
[src:immune-response/antigen] This includes parts (coats, capsules, cell walls, flagella, fimbriae, and toxins) of bacteria, viruses, and other microorganisms.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Non-microbial non-self antigens can include pollen, egg white, and proteins from transplanted tissues and organs or on the surface of transfused blood cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Antigen-presenting cells present antigens in the form of peptides on major histocompatibility complexes.
[src:immune-response/antigen] All nucleated cells (i.e., all cells except for red blood cells) express MHC class I, which samples peptides from the cytosol, defaulting to presenting self-antigen (unless something foreign ends up in the cytosol or if the cell is capable of cross-presentation).
[src:immune-response/antigen] Antigens originating from outside the cell make their way into the endomembrane system via processes like phagocytosis, endocytosis, or macropinocytosis and are loaded onto MHC class II molecules.
[src:immune-response/antigen] In contrast to MHC class I, MHC class II is expressed on a limited subset of cells, the vast majority of which are immune cells (some epithelial cells at mucosal surfaces may also express MHC class II).
[src:immune-response/antigen] Often, when people refer to antigen-presenting cells, they are actually referring to professional antigen-presenting cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Professional antigen-presenting cells refer to B cells, dendritic cells, Langerhans cells, and macrophages, all of which express MHC class II and have the ability to activate naive T cells (other antigen-presenting cells cannot supply naive T cells with all the signals required for activation).
[src:immune-response/antigen] The MHC locus is the most polymorphic region of the entire human genome, and it is responsible for the presentation of antigens to T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen] This extensive polymorphism provides population-level protection by increasing the likelihood that some individuals will mount effective immune responses against novel pathogens, thus helping to ensure species survival during epidemics.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Cheetahs, for example, underwent a bottleneck event 10,000 years ago that greatly limited the diversity of their MHC locus and as a result, show increased susceptibility to infectious diseases, though this represents one of multiple factors affecting their conservation status.
[src:immune-response/antigen] CD4 T cells (in general, helper T cells) are able to recognize MHC class II molecules using CD4, and their T-cell receptor recognizes the specific peptide-MHC complex sequence.
[src:immune-response/antigen] In contrast, CD8 T cells (in general, killer T cells) are able to recognize MHC class I molecules through the α3 domain of MHC class I (it does not recognize β2 microglobulin).
[src:immune-response/antigen] T cell receptors are, in general, highly specific to particular peptide-MHC complexes.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Some peptide sequences can only be presented by a specific type of MHC protein because they require specific amino acid sequences within the binding groove to associate with them.
[src:immune-response/antigen] These are known as MHC-restricted peptides.
[src:immune-response/antigen] If an individual does not express the relevant MHC protein needed for a given MHC-restricted peptide, they will not be able to present that antigen to T cells.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Because the T cell receptor cannot recognize anything not presented on an MHC, conventional (see next paragraph) T cells are not capable of responding to non-peptide antigens (lipids, carbohydrates, etc), except in the case of post-translational modifications to peptides that end up being presented.
[src:immune-response/antigen] However, attaching the polysaccharide to a carrier protein (especially an immunogenic one, such as tetanus toxoid) enables B cells that recognize the polysaccharide to get help from T cells that recognize the carrier protein's peptides.
[src:immune-response/antigen] These are known as conjugate vaccines or glycoconjugates.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Moreover, the processing of an antigen by an antigen-presenting cell causes loss of the tertiary structure of the protein, meaning that T cells recognize linear epitopes only (the amino acids recognized have to be next to each other in the primary structure).
[src:immune-response/antigen] There are also subsets of T cells known as unconventional T cells that may recognize non-peptide antigens, or peptides.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Many of these subsets show predominantly innate, rather than adaptive, functions.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Mucosa-associated invariant T cells (MAIT) cells recognize ligands presented by the MHC-related protein MR1, which presents metabolites of riboflavin, pyridoxine, and folates.
[src:immune-response/antigen] NKT cells recognize glycolipid antigens presented on CD1d, most prominently α-galactosylceramide.
[src:immune-response/antigen] At the molecular level, an antigen can be characterized by its ability to bind to an antibody's paratopes.
[src:immune-response/antigen] Different antibodies have the potential to discriminate among specific epitopes present on the antigen surface.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] An **immune response** is a physiological reaction which occurs within an organism in the context of inflammation for the purpose of defending against exogenous factors.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] These include a wide variety of different toxins, viruses, intra- and extracellular bacteria, protozoa, helminths, and fungi which could cause serious problems to the health of the host organism if not cleared from the body.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] In addition, there are other forms of immune response.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] For example, harmless exogenous factors (such as pollen and food components) can trigger allergy; latex and metals are also known allergens.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] A transplanted tissue (for example, blood) or organ can cause graft-versus-host disease.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] A type of immune reactivity known as Rh disease can be observed in pregnant women.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] These special forms of immune response are classified as hypersensitivity.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Another special form of immune response is antitumor immunity.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] In general, there are two branches of the immune response, created by the innate immune system and the adaptive immune system respectively, which work together to protect against pathogens.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Both branches engage humoral and cellular components.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The innate branch—the body's first reaction to an invader—is known to be a non-specific and quick response to any sort of pathogen .
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Components of the innate immune response include physical barriers like the skin and mucous membranes, immune cells such as neutrophils, macrophages, and monocytes, and soluble factors including cytokines and complement.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] On the other hand, the adaptive branch is the body's immune response which is catered against specific antigens and thus, it takes longer to activate the components involved.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The adaptive branch include cells such as dendritic cells, T cell, and B cells as well as antibodies—also known as immunoglobulins—which directly interact with antigen and are a very important component for a strong response against an invader.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The first contact that an organism has with a particular antigen will result in the production of effector T and B cells which are activated cells that defend against the pathogen.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The production of these effector cells as a result of the first-time exposure is called a **primary** immune response.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Memory T and memory B cells are also produced in the case that the same pathogen enters the organism again.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] If the organism does happen to become re-exposed to the same pathogen, a **secondary** immune response will kick in and the immune system will be able to respond in both a fast and strong manner because of the memory cells from the first exposure.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Vaccines introduce a weakened, killed, or fragmented microorganism in order to evoke a primary immune response.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] This is so that in the case that an exposure to the real pathogen occurs, the body can rely on the secondary immune response to quickly defend against it.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The innate immune response is an organism's first response to foreign invaders.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] This immune response is evolutionarily conserved across many different species, with all multi-cellular organisms having some sort of variation of an innate response.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The innate immune system consists of physical barriers such as skin and mucous membranes, various cell types like neutrophils, macrophages, and monocytes, and soluble factors including cytokines and complement.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] In contrast to the adaptive immune response, the innate response is not specific to any one foreign invader and as a result, works quickly to rid the body of pathogens.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Pathogens are recognized and detected via pattern recognition receptors (PRR).
[src:immune-response/immune-response] These receptors are structures on the surface of macrophages which are capable of binding foreign invaders and thus initiating cell signaling within the immune cell.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Specifically, the PRRs identify pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) which are integral structural components of pathogens.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Examples of PAMPs include the peptidoglycan cell wall or lipopolysaccharides (LPS), both of which are essential components of bacteria and are therefore evolutionarily conserved across many different bacterial species.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] When a foreign pathogen bypasses the physical barriers and enters an organism, the PRRs on macrophages will recognize and bind to specific PAMPs.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] This binding results in the activation of a signaling pathway which allows for the transcription factor NF-κB to enter the nucleus of the macrophage and initiate the transcription and eventual secretion of various cytokines such as IL-8, IL-1, and TNFα.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Release of these cytokines is necessary for the entry of neutrophils from the blood vessels to the infected tissue.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Once neutrophils enter the tissue, like macrophages, they are able to phagocytize and kill any pathogens or microbes.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Complement, another component of the innate immune system, consists of three pathways that are activated in distinct ways.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The classical pathway is triggered when IgG or IgM is bound to its target antigen on either the pathogen cell membrane or an antigen-bound antibody.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The alternative pathway is activated by foreign surfaces such as viruses, fungi, bacteria, parasites, etc., and is capable of autoactivation due to “tickover” of C3.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The lectin pathway is triggered when mannose-binding lectin (MBL) or ficolin aka specific pattern recognition receptors bind to pathogen-associated molecular patterns on the surface of invading microorganisms such as yeast, bacteria, parasites, and viruses.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Each of the three pathways ensures that complement will still be functional if one pathway ceases to work or a foreign invader is able to evade one of these pathways (defense in depth principle).
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Though the pathways are activated differently, the overall role of the complement system is to opsonize pathogens and induce a series of inflammatory responses that help to combat infection.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The adaptive immune response is the body's second line of defense.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The cells of the adaptive immune system are extremely specific because during early developmental stages the B and T cells develop antigen receptors that are specific to only certain antigens.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] This is extremely important for B and T cell activation.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] B and T cells are extremely dangerous cells, and if they are able to attack without undergoing a rigorous process of activation, a faulty B or T cell can begin exterminating the host's own healthy cells.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Activation of naïve helper T cells occurs when antigen-presenting cells (APCs) present foreign antigen via MHC class II molecules on their cell surface.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] These APCs include dendritic cells, B cells, and macrophages which are specially equipped not only with MHC class II but also with co-stimulatory ligands which are recognized by co-stimulatory receptors on helper T cells.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Without the co-stimulatory molecules, the adaptive immune response would be inefficient and T cells would become anergic.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Several T cell subgroups can be activated by specific APCs, and each T cell is specially equipped to deal with each unique microbial pathogen.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The type of T cell activated and the type of response generated depends, in part, on the context in which the APC first encountered the antigen.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Once helper T cells are activated, they are able to activate naïve B cells in the lymph node.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] However, B cell activation is a two-step process.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Firstly, B cell receptors, which are just Immunoglobulin M (IgM) and Immunoglobulin D (IgD) antibodies specific to the particular B cell, must bind to the antigen which then results in internal processing so that it is presented on the MHC class II molecules of the B cell.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Once this happens a T helper cell which is able to identify the antigen bound to the MHC interacts with its co-stimulatory molecule and activates the B cell.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] As a result, the B cell becomes a plasma cell which secretes antibodies that act as an opsonin against invaders.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Specificity in the adaptive branch is due to the fact that every B and T cell is different.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Thus there is a diverse community of cells ready to recognize and attack a full range of invaders.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] The trade-off, however, is that the adaptive immune response is much slower than the body's innate response because its cells are extremely specific and activation is required before it is able to actually act.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] In addition to specificity, the adaptive immune response is also known for immunological memory.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] After encountering an antigen, the immune system produces memory T and B cells which allow for a speedier, more robust immune response in the case that the organism ever encounters the same antigen again.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Depending on exogenous demands, several types of immune response (IR) are distinguished.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] In this paradigm, immune system (both innate and adaptive) and non-immune system cellular and molecular components are organized to optimally respond to distinct exposome challenges.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Currently, several types of IR are classified.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] Additional types of IR can be observed in noninfectious pathologies.
[src:immune-response/immune-response] All types of IR have *sensor* (ILCs, NK cells), *adaptive* (T and B cells), and *effector* (neutrophils, eosinophils, basophils, mast cells) parts.
